WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.430 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:02.430 --> 00:00:04.374 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:04.374 --> 00:00:07.290 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:07.290 --> 00:00:10.538 align:middle line:90%


00:00:10.538 --> 00:00:12.330 align:middle line:84%
ERIC DEMAINE: All right,
let's get started.

00:00:12.330 --> 00:00:14.100 align:middle line:90%
Welcome back to 6.1200.

00:00:14.100 --> 00:00:18.540 align:middle line:84%
I am the second of the three
lecturers in this class.

00:00:18.540 --> 00:00:20.570 align:middle line:90%
You can call me Eric.

00:00:20.570 --> 00:00:23.090 align:middle line:84%
And Brynmor will
be on next week.

00:00:23.090 --> 00:00:26.810 align:middle line:84%
So today we are going to
continue our theme of induction

00:00:26.810 --> 00:00:30.210 align:middle line:84%
and prove some even cooler and
stronger forms of induction.

00:00:30.210 --> 00:00:33.360 align:middle line:84%
Just a recap of where
we were last time,

00:00:33.360 --> 00:00:37.310 align:middle line:84%
as we've seen, we're growing
our catalog of different proof

00:00:37.310 --> 00:00:40.700 align:middle line:84%
techniques of how to prove
different types of theorems,

00:00:40.700 --> 00:00:42.960 align:middle line:90%
almost by like a cookbook.

00:00:42.960 --> 00:00:45.330 align:middle line:84%
If you want to cook this,
here's how you get started.

00:00:45.330 --> 00:00:48.150 align:middle line:84%
And so here's a brief
summary of this.

00:00:48.150 --> 00:00:50.310 align:middle line:84%
If the theorem you want
to prove starts with,

00:00:50.310 --> 00:00:53.660 align:middle line:84%
"there exists something," then
a natural way to prove that is

00:00:53.660 --> 00:00:55.470 align:middle line:90%
by example or by construction.

00:00:55.470 --> 00:01:00.470 align:middle line:84%
You construct a particular x
star and prove that P of x star

00:01:00.470 --> 00:01:01.320 align:middle line:90%
is true.

00:01:01.320 --> 00:01:03.170 align:middle line:84%
And if you can do
that, then you've

00:01:03.170 --> 00:01:05.700 align:middle line:84%
proved that there exists
an x, where P of x is true.

00:01:05.700 --> 00:01:07.800 align:middle line:84%
It's straightforward,
but it lets you unwrap--

00:01:07.800 --> 00:01:10.050 align:middle line:84%
if I give you an expression
that starts with "exists,"

00:01:10.050 --> 00:01:12.680 align:middle line:84%
then you know your first step
is try to figure out an x where

00:01:12.680 --> 00:01:14.540 align:middle line:90%
this is true.

00:01:14.540 --> 00:01:17.300 align:middle line:84%
And of course, to prove
P of x star you probably

00:01:17.300 --> 00:01:19.920 align:middle line:90%
recursively use this cookbook.

00:01:19.920 --> 00:01:22.430 align:middle line:84%
If you want to
prove a universal,

00:01:22.430 --> 00:01:26.750 align:middle line:84%
one common way-- if you want to
prove for all x, P of x is true,

00:01:26.750 --> 00:01:29.640 align:middle line:84%
typically your first line
is take an arbitrary x.

00:01:29.640 --> 00:01:31.160 align:middle line:90%
Just give it a name, x.

00:01:31.160 --> 00:01:33.560 align:middle line:84%
And then prove that P
of x is true no matter

00:01:33.560 --> 00:01:34.560 align:middle line:90%
what x you started with.

00:01:34.560 --> 00:01:37.370 align:middle line:84%
Therefore, it's true
for all of them.

00:01:37.370 --> 00:01:38.970 align:middle line:84%
Come back to
induction in a second.

00:01:38.970 --> 00:01:41.730 align:middle line:84%
If the main thing you want
to prove is an implication,

00:01:41.730 --> 00:01:45.150 align:middle line:84%
P implies Q, this
is if P then Q.

00:01:45.150 --> 00:01:48.410 align:middle line:84%
And I want to remind
you that P implies

00:01:48.410 --> 00:01:57.140 align:middle line:84%
Q is the same thing as not P or
Q. We'll use this a bunch today.

00:01:57.140 --> 00:01:59.700 align:middle line:84%
Then the direct
way to prove this,

00:01:59.700 --> 00:02:02.390 align:middle line:84%
what we call a direct
argument, is assume P is true,

00:02:02.390 --> 00:02:04.045 align:middle line:90%
and then prove Q is true.

00:02:04.045 --> 00:02:05.420 align:middle line:84%
Because this
implication, we only

00:02:05.420 --> 00:02:07.970 align:middle line:84%
need to prove that Q
is true when P is true.

00:02:07.970 --> 00:02:10.639 align:middle line:90%
If P, then Q.

00:02:10.639 --> 00:02:14.450 align:middle line:84%
Or another way to prove that
same statement, P implies Q,

00:02:14.450 --> 00:02:16.290 align:middle line:84%
is what's called
the contrapositive.

00:02:16.290 --> 00:02:18.860 align:middle line:84%
It turns out P implies Q is
the same statement-- it's

00:02:18.860 --> 00:02:23.010 align:middle line:84%
equivalent to not Q
implies not P. Remember,

00:02:23.010 --> 00:02:26.330 align:middle line:90%
this symbol is a negation.

00:02:26.330 --> 00:02:27.900 align:middle line:90%
Flip true and false.

00:02:27.900 --> 00:02:30.120 align:middle line:84%
So to do that with
a direct argument,

00:02:30.120 --> 00:02:34.440 align:middle line:84%
we would prove that if not Q
is true, then not P is true.

00:02:34.440 --> 00:02:38.300 align:middle line:84%
In other words, assume not
Q, and then prove not P.

00:02:38.300 --> 00:02:40.230 align:middle line:90%
This may seem magical.

00:02:40.230 --> 00:02:43.980 align:middle line:84%
Why is P implies Q the same
as not Q implies not P?

00:02:43.980 --> 00:02:47.670 align:middle line:84%
But it actually follows
directly from this equivalence.

00:02:47.670 --> 00:02:55.770 align:middle line:84%
If you look at not Q implies not
P, this is the same thing as--

00:02:55.770 --> 00:03:01.350 align:middle line:84%
let me go over here-- not
not Q or not P, all right,

00:03:01.350 --> 00:03:02.570 align:middle line:90%
because it implies--

00:03:02.570 --> 00:03:05.580 align:middle line:84%
it's the same thing as taking
an or if you negate the first--

00:03:05.580 --> 00:03:07.100 align:middle line:90%
the part on the left.

00:03:07.100 --> 00:03:11.250 align:middle line:84%
And not not Q is
the same as Q, OK?

00:03:11.250 --> 00:03:17.030 align:middle line:84%
So this was not Q implies not
P. It's the same thing as.

00:03:17.030 --> 00:03:18.330 align:middle line:90%
This is the same thing as this.

00:03:18.330 --> 00:03:23.250 align:middle line:84%
And that is exactly this just by
switching the order of the ORs.

00:03:23.250 --> 00:03:28.380 align:middle line:84%
And so P implies Q is the same
thing as not Q implies not P.

00:03:28.380 --> 00:03:29.820 align:middle line:90%
So that was contrapositive.

00:03:29.820 --> 00:03:31.790 align:middle line:84%
There was a related
notion of contradiction,

00:03:31.790 --> 00:03:36.140 align:middle line:84%
where if you want to
prove any statement P,

00:03:36.140 --> 00:03:40.860 align:middle line:84%
you assume that not P is true
and then find a contradiction.

00:03:40.860 --> 00:03:42.960 align:middle line:84%
Prove that in fact
false is true,

00:03:42.960 --> 00:03:44.880 align:middle line:84%
or something is
both true and false.

00:03:44.880 --> 00:03:47.090 align:middle line:84%
All these things
are very, very bad

00:03:47.090 --> 00:03:49.980 align:middle line:84%
because we assume that
our axioms are consistent.

00:03:49.980 --> 00:03:53.290 align:middle line:84%
And so if you can prove false,
that means that what you assumed

00:03:53.290 --> 00:03:56.080 align:middle line:90%
must also be false.

00:03:56.080 --> 00:03:58.420 align:middle line:84%
And so if not P is false,
that's the same thing

00:03:58.420 --> 00:03:59.660 align:middle line:90%
as saying P is true.

00:03:59.660 --> 00:04:00.660 align:middle line:90%
It feels very backwards.

00:04:00.660 --> 00:04:02.077 align:middle line:84%
Lots of double
negatives in there.

00:04:02.077 --> 00:04:03.770 align:middle line:84%
But that's the nature
of contradiction.

00:04:03.770 --> 00:04:04.970 align:middle line:84%
We try to avoid
them when we can,

00:04:04.970 --> 00:04:07.428 align:middle line:84%
but sometimes it's really the
right way to prove something.

00:04:07.428 --> 00:04:10.060 align:middle line:84%
And the last technique
we saw was induction,

00:04:10.060 --> 00:04:12.160 align:middle line:84%
where if we have a
universal quantifier

00:04:12.160 --> 00:04:14.740 align:middle line:84%
over the natural numbers,
we want to prove P of n

00:04:14.740 --> 00:04:18.010 align:middle line:84%
is true for all natural
numbers 0, 1, 2, 3, and so on,

00:04:18.010 --> 00:04:21.589 align:middle line:84%
then we only need to prove it
for some base case, P of 0.

00:04:21.589 --> 00:04:24.400 align:middle line:84%
And then we need to prove
that P of n implies P of n

00:04:24.400 --> 00:04:26.260 align:middle line:90%
plus 1 for all n.

00:04:26.260 --> 00:04:28.965 align:middle line:84%
So we'll talk more about
induction in a little bit.

00:04:28.965 --> 00:04:31.540 align:middle line:90%


00:04:31.540 --> 00:04:36.290 align:middle line:84%
Today we're going to add to this
list two more proof techniques.

00:04:36.290 --> 00:04:39.980 align:middle line:84%
One is proof by cases, and
the other is strong induction.

00:04:39.980 --> 00:04:42.280 align:middle line:84%
So proof by cases is just
a nice general technique

00:04:42.280 --> 00:04:43.930 align:middle line:90%
to be aware of.

00:04:43.930 --> 00:04:45.950 align:middle line:90%
It can be very powerful.

00:04:45.950 --> 00:04:48.370 align:middle line:84%
Strong induction is going
to be an even cooler

00:04:48.370 --> 00:04:51.130 align:middle line:90%
form of induction.

00:04:51.130 --> 00:04:55.010 align:middle line:84%
All right, but we'll start
today with proof by cases.

00:04:55.010 --> 00:04:57.693 align:middle line:84%
And we'll start with
proof by 2 cases.

00:04:57.693 --> 00:05:05.110 align:middle line:90%


00:05:05.110 --> 00:05:07.605 align:middle line:84%
And then we'll generalize
to more than two cases.

00:05:07.605 --> 00:05:11.080 align:middle line:90%


00:05:11.080 --> 00:05:20.500 align:middle line:84%
So the idea is take
any proposition C,

00:05:20.500 --> 00:05:32.730 align:middle line:84%
and observe that C or not C is a
tautology, meaning always true.

00:05:32.730 --> 00:05:37.330 align:middle line:90%


00:05:37.330 --> 00:05:41.660 align:middle line:84%
If C is true, then this whole
thing is true because C is true.

00:05:41.660 --> 00:05:44.360 align:middle line:84%
If C is false,
then not C is true.

00:05:44.360 --> 00:05:45.980 align:middle line:90%
And so this whole thing is true.

00:05:45.980 --> 00:05:50.620 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to remind you
this V symbol is an "or."

00:05:50.620 --> 00:05:55.390 align:middle line:84%
Whereas, the opposite
symbol is an "and."

00:05:55.390 --> 00:05:58.930 align:middle line:84%
I think the mnemonic here is
this looks like a letter A. This

00:05:58.930 --> 00:06:02.440 align:middle line:84%
looks like a letter O. I've
heard some people say this looks

00:06:02.440 --> 00:06:05.020 align:middle line:90%
like a lowercase r for "or."

00:06:05.020 --> 00:06:07.190 align:middle line:84%
Anyway, you just
remember these things.

00:06:07.190 --> 00:06:07.840 align:middle line:90%
This is "or."

00:06:07.840 --> 00:06:09.730 align:middle line:90%
This is "and."

00:06:09.730 --> 00:06:14.600 align:middle line:84%
So C or not C is the question,
though, is always true.

00:06:14.600 --> 00:06:17.950 align:middle line:84%
So we call it a tautology, fancy
word for being always true.

00:06:17.950 --> 00:06:23.710 align:middle line:84%
And so what this tells us
is that our proposition P--

00:06:23.710 --> 00:06:25.750 align:middle line:90%
let's say we want to prove P--

00:06:25.750 --> 00:06:39.640 align:middle line:84%
is equivalent to C or not C
implies P. So this is saying

00:06:39.640 --> 00:06:43.300 align:middle line:90%
if C or not C, then P is true.

00:06:43.300 --> 00:06:44.990 align:middle line:90%
C or not C is just always true.

00:06:44.990 --> 00:06:47.450 align:middle line:84%
So this is saying if true--
in other words always--

00:06:47.450 --> 00:06:49.430 align:middle line:90%
P better be true.

00:06:49.430 --> 00:06:52.320 align:middle line:84%
So P and this implication
are equivalent.

00:06:52.320 --> 00:06:55.310 align:middle line:84%
Another way to see that is
to rewrite this implication

00:06:55.310 --> 00:06:59.150 align:middle line:90%
as a negation.

00:06:59.150 --> 00:07:05.930 align:middle line:84%
So this is like
saying not true or P.

00:07:05.930 --> 00:07:13.670 align:middle line:84%
And so that's just the same
thing as P because this is true.

00:07:13.670 --> 00:07:15.170 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:07:15.170 --> 00:07:16.160 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:07:16.160 --> 00:07:18.200 align:middle line:84%
So I want to rewrite
this a little bit

00:07:18.200 --> 00:07:24.920 align:middle line:84%
and say this thing is equivalent
to C implies P and not C implies

00:07:24.920 --> 00:07:29.480 align:middle line:90%
P.

00:07:29.480 --> 00:07:31.610 align:middle line:90%
Why is this true?

00:07:31.610 --> 00:07:33.290 align:middle line:90%
It's like a distributive law.

00:07:33.290 --> 00:07:36.300 align:middle line:84%
This is saying I want to
prove that C implies P,

00:07:36.300 --> 00:07:39.120 align:middle line:84%
and I want to prove
that not C implies P.

00:07:39.120 --> 00:07:40.500 align:middle line:90%
That's what I wrote over there.

00:07:40.500 --> 00:07:43.580 align:middle line:84%
That implies that the
combination of C and not C

00:07:43.580 --> 00:07:48.485 align:middle line:84%
implies P. OK, so I claim
these are equivalent.

00:07:48.485 --> 00:07:50.360 align:middle line:84%
One way to verify it is
with the truth table,

00:07:50.360 --> 00:07:53.110 align:middle line:84%
or you can do it with
some manipulation.

00:07:53.110 --> 00:07:58.030 align:middle line:90%
All right, so we have--

00:07:58.030 --> 00:07:59.950 align:middle line:84%
what this is saying
is in order to prove

00:07:59.950 --> 00:08:02.830 align:middle line:84%
P we need to prove that
P is true assuming C

00:08:02.830 --> 00:08:05.540 align:middle line:84%
and prove that P is
true assuming not C.

00:08:05.540 --> 00:08:08.960 align:middle line:84%
And these are the two
cases in a proof by cases.

00:08:08.960 --> 00:08:11.085 align:middle line:84%
Let me write out a
little template for you.

00:08:11.085 --> 00:08:15.520 align:middle line:90%


00:08:15.520 --> 00:08:17.350 align:middle line:84%
Let's suppose the
theorem we want

00:08:17.350 --> 00:08:27.280 align:middle line:84%
to prove is P. Theorem
means something that's true

00:08:27.280 --> 00:08:30.550 align:middle line:90%
and that we're about to prove.

00:08:30.550 --> 00:08:35.763 align:middle line:84%
And so we usually say proof
by cases on the truth value.

00:08:35.763 --> 00:08:39.580 align:middle line:90%


00:08:39.580 --> 00:08:43.563 align:middle line:90%
Of C. So this is for any.

00:08:43.563 --> 00:08:48.010 align:middle line:90%


00:08:48.010 --> 00:08:53.590 align:middle line:84%
Statement C. Proposition is
what the word I was looking for.

00:08:53.590 --> 00:08:55.995 align:middle line:84%
Any Proposition C, it's
either true or false.

00:08:55.995 --> 00:08:59.093 align:middle line:90%


00:08:59.093 --> 00:09:01.510 align:middle line:84%
And so we're going to do proof
by cases on the truth value

00:09:01.510 --> 00:09:08.140 align:middle line:90%
of C. Case 1 is that C is true.

00:09:08.140 --> 00:09:11.220 align:middle line:90%
And case 2 is that C is false.

00:09:11.220 --> 00:09:16.510 align:middle line:90%


00:09:16.510 --> 00:09:18.880 align:middle line:84%
And so what do we
do in each case?

00:09:18.880 --> 00:09:20.810 align:middle line:84%
Well, in the case
that C is true,

00:09:20.810 --> 00:09:23.835 align:middle line:84%
this means that we get
to assume that C is true.

00:09:23.835 --> 00:09:30.010 align:middle line:90%


00:09:30.010 --> 00:09:32.390 align:middle line:84%
And then use that to
prove that P is true.

00:09:32.390 --> 00:09:37.810 align:middle line:84%
And so the missing step in this
proof outline or this template

00:09:37.810 --> 00:09:43.110 align:middle line:84%
is we need to say P is true
because some reasons, which

00:09:43.110 --> 00:09:44.940 align:middle line:90%
we need to fill in.

00:09:44.940 --> 00:09:48.490 align:middle line:84%
And similarly, in
the C is false case,

00:09:48.490 --> 00:09:54.990 align:middle line:84%
we need to prove P is
true for some reasons.

00:09:54.990 --> 00:09:57.220 align:middle line:84%
So we need twice
as many reasons,

00:09:57.220 --> 00:09:59.340 align:middle line:84%
but the idea is that
maybe assuming C is true

00:09:59.340 --> 00:10:00.910 align:middle line:84%
makes it easier to
prove P is true.

00:10:00.910 --> 00:10:04.620 align:middle line:84%
Maybe also assuming C
is false makes it easier

00:10:04.620 --> 00:10:06.550 align:middle line:90%
to prove that P is true.

00:10:06.550 --> 00:10:09.850 align:middle line:84%
So in these boxes
here we get to use C.

00:10:09.850 --> 00:10:13.200 align:middle line:84%
And in here, we
get to use not C.

00:10:13.200 --> 00:10:15.130 align:middle line:84%
And often, this
makes proofs easier.

00:10:15.130 --> 00:10:16.860 align:middle line:84%
But the challenging
part is to pick

00:10:16.860 --> 00:10:22.350 align:middle line:84%
the correct C. What's the right
choice of C for this to be true?

00:10:22.350 --> 00:10:26.250 align:middle line:84%
And maybe one more line I want
to add to this template, which

00:10:26.250 --> 00:10:29.400 align:middle line:84%
is pretty obvious in
the setting but gets

00:10:29.400 --> 00:10:32.490 align:middle line:84%
much less obvious when you
think about more than two cases.

00:10:32.490 --> 00:10:35.640 align:middle line:84%
So a final step in
this proof would

00:10:35.640 --> 00:10:41.580 align:middle line:84%
be to say C is either true or
false because all propositions

00:10:41.580 --> 00:10:44.610 align:middle line:90%
are either true or false.

00:10:44.610 --> 00:10:50.790 align:middle line:90%
And so the cases are exhaustive.

00:10:50.790 --> 00:10:54.090 align:middle line:84%
So this is also called
a proof by exhaustion

00:10:54.090 --> 00:10:55.480 align:middle line:90%
because we're really tired.

00:10:55.480 --> 00:10:56.710 align:middle line:90%
Maybe we are also.

00:10:56.710 --> 00:10:59.650 align:middle line:84%
But the idea is we want to
exhaust all possible cases.

00:10:59.650 --> 00:11:03.240 align:middle line:84%
And if we prove that we captured
every possible situation and all

00:11:03.240 --> 00:11:06.030 align:middle line:84%
of them P is true,
then we're done.

00:11:06.030 --> 00:11:08.260 align:middle line:90%
So that's what we'd like to do.

00:11:08.260 --> 00:11:09.730 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to give
you two examples.

00:11:09.730 --> 00:11:11.260 align:middle line:90%
First one is very simple.

00:11:11.260 --> 00:11:13.840 align:middle line:84%
The second one is
more interesting.

00:11:13.840 --> 00:11:18.990 align:middle line:90%


00:11:18.990 --> 00:11:19.980 align:middle line:90%
Questions?

00:11:19.980 --> 00:11:20.480 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:11:20.480 --> 00:11:37.410 align:middle line:90%


00:11:37.410 --> 00:11:42.450 align:middle line:84%
So the claim is, this is a
general fact, that A implies B

00:11:42.450 --> 00:11:45.940 align:middle line:90%
or B implies C is a tautology.

00:11:45.940 --> 00:11:47.950 align:middle line:90%
So this means it's always true.

00:11:47.950 --> 00:11:51.160 align:middle line:84%
Again, so you can rewrite
this as for all A,

00:11:51.160 --> 00:11:58.860 align:middle line:84%
B, and C, which are
either true or false,

00:11:58.860 --> 00:12:05.780 align:middle line:84%
we have that A implies B
or B implies C is true.

00:12:05.780 --> 00:12:08.400 align:middle line:90%


00:12:08.400 --> 00:12:09.930 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:12:09.930 --> 00:12:12.750 align:middle line:90%
Fun facts.

00:12:12.750 --> 00:12:14.550 align:middle line:90%
Let's prove it.

00:12:14.550 --> 00:12:16.920 align:middle line:84%
And the proof
technique we're going

00:12:16.920 --> 00:12:23.550 align:middle line:84%
to use by cases, by two
cases, namely, on B. B

00:12:23.550 --> 00:12:26.210 align:middle line:90%
is either true or false.

00:12:26.210 --> 00:12:30.360 align:middle line:90%


00:12:30.360 --> 00:12:33.000 align:middle line:84%
We could try to do a case
analysis in terms of A

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:36.135 align:middle line:84%
or in terms of C. It turns out
B is the right answer here.

00:12:36.135 --> 00:12:37.510 align:middle line:84%
It will lead to
the fewest cases.

00:12:37.510 --> 00:12:40.320 align:middle line:84%
We'll only need two,
intuitively because B is

00:12:40.320 --> 00:12:41.770 align:middle line:90%
in both of these expressions.

00:12:41.770 --> 00:12:44.370 align:middle line:84%
So it seems good to split
on B because it will

00:12:44.370 --> 00:12:47.370 align:middle line:90%
impact this one and this one.

00:12:47.370 --> 00:12:48.666 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:12:48.666 --> 00:12:55.100 align:middle line:90%
So case 1 is that B is true.

00:12:55.100 --> 00:13:02.942 align:middle line:90%


00:13:02.942 --> 00:13:09.750 align:middle line:84%
If B is true, I claim
that A implies B is true,

00:13:09.750 --> 00:13:13.110 align:middle line:90%
which is this first half.

00:13:13.110 --> 00:13:15.330 align:middle line:90%
Why?

00:13:15.330 --> 00:13:21.690 align:middle line:84%
In other words, I claim that
A implies true is a tautology.

00:13:21.690 --> 00:13:24.150 align:middle line:84%
I think another-- again,
an easy way to see this

00:13:24.150 --> 00:13:28.830 align:middle line:84%
is to rewrite this implication
as not the left-hand side

00:13:28.830 --> 00:13:32.890 align:middle line:84%
or the right-hand
side, not A or true.

00:13:32.890 --> 00:13:34.150 align:middle line:90%
Well, that's just true.

00:13:34.150 --> 00:13:36.780 align:middle line:90%
True or anything is true.

00:13:36.780 --> 00:13:40.770 align:middle line:84%
So in particular,
over here, not A or B

00:13:40.770 --> 00:13:45.060 align:middle line:84%
is true because we just
assumed that B is true.

00:13:45.060 --> 00:13:52.680 align:middle line:84%
So this tells us that A implies
B, or anything, in particular B

00:13:52.680 --> 00:13:56.730 align:middle line:90%
or C, is also true.

00:13:56.730 --> 00:13:59.260 align:middle line:90%
So kind of trivial, right?

00:13:59.260 --> 00:14:01.720 align:middle line:84%
If you assume B is true,
then, of course, this is true.

00:14:01.720 --> 00:14:04.560 align:middle line:84%
And so, of course, the
whole thing is true.

00:14:04.560 --> 00:14:07.170 align:middle line:84%
So easy when you have
the correct case.

00:14:07.170 --> 00:14:08.860 align:middle line:84%
Let's think about
the other case.

00:14:08.860 --> 00:14:12.010 align:middle line:84%
It's not enough to just
have one half of the cases.

00:14:12.010 --> 00:14:13.955 align:middle line:84%
We also need to think
about when B is false.

00:14:13.955 --> 00:14:17.130 align:middle line:90%


00:14:17.130 --> 00:14:20.590 align:middle line:84%
When B is false, I claim
that the other term is true.

00:14:20.590 --> 00:14:25.307 align:middle line:84%
I claim that B
implies C is true.

00:14:25.307 --> 00:14:26.890 align:middle line:84%
This is maybe a
little less intuitive.

00:14:26.890 --> 00:14:29.370 align:middle line:84%
This is saying
that false implies

00:14:29.370 --> 00:14:35.340 align:middle line:84%
C is a tautology, like for
any C, false implies it.

00:14:35.340 --> 00:14:37.710 align:middle line:84%
And this should eventually
become intuitive for you

00:14:37.710 --> 00:14:39.940 align:middle line:84%
when you get used to
implies and if then.

00:14:39.940 --> 00:14:43.380 align:middle line:84%
This is saying if false,
which means never,

00:14:43.380 --> 00:14:45.810 align:middle line:90%
I need C to be true.

00:14:45.810 --> 00:14:48.940 align:middle line:84%
But if this condition
is never true,

00:14:48.940 --> 00:14:51.040 align:middle line:84%
then I don't care about
the right-hand side.

00:14:51.040 --> 00:14:56.590 align:middle line:84%
If it's if-- if pigs
fly, then, I don't know,

00:14:56.590 --> 00:14:59.580 align:middle line:90%
apples are orange or something.

00:14:59.580 --> 00:15:01.830 align:middle line:84%
That's a true statement
because it will never

00:15:01.830 --> 00:15:04.600 align:middle line:84%
be the case that pigs fly, or
at least in the present time.

00:15:04.600 --> 00:15:09.160 align:middle line:84%
So another way to see that
is to think about, again,

00:15:09.160 --> 00:15:12.580 align:middle line:90%
not B or C. B is false.

00:15:12.580 --> 00:15:14.610 align:middle line:90%
So not B is true.

00:15:14.610 --> 00:15:18.570 align:middle line:84%
And so, of course,
true or C is also true.

00:15:18.570 --> 00:15:23.220 align:middle line:84%
And so that tells us
that anything or B

00:15:23.220 --> 00:15:27.120 align:middle line:90%
implies C is also true.

00:15:27.120 --> 00:15:30.085 align:middle line:84%
So in other words,
this statement,

00:15:30.085 --> 00:15:40.250 align:middle line:84%
which maybe I'll call P, I'll
say in either case P is true.

00:15:40.250 --> 00:15:42.870 align:middle line:84%
And so I write my little
end of proof symbol.

00:15:42.870 --> 00:15:45.050 align:middle line:90%
This is QED from last time.

00:15:45.050 --> 00:15:48.010 align:middle line:84%
This means that I have
demonstrated the theorem.

00:15:48.010 --> 00:15:50.900 align:middle line:90%


00:15:50.900 --> 00:15:51.890 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:15:51.890 --> 00:15:54.057 align:middle line:84%
So in one case, this
part was trivial.

00:15:54.057 --> 00:15:56.640 align:middle line:84%
In the other case, this part was
trivial because it's an "or."

00:15:56.640 --> 00:15:58.460 align:middle line:84%
We're happy in either
case, and we've

00:15:58.460 --> 00:16:01.280 align:middle line:90%
done our first proof by cases.

00:16:01.280 --> 00:16:02.900 align:middle line:90%
Pretty straightforward.

00:16:02.900 --> 00:16:07.220 align:middle line:84%
Let's do a more
surprising result

00:16:07.220 --> 00:16:13.450 align:middle line:84%
using proof by cases called
mutual friends and strangers.

00:16:13.450 --> 00:16:16.580 align:middle line:90%


00:16:16.580 --> 00:16:18.860 align:middle line:84%
This is actually a famous
mathematical problem.

00:16:18.860 --> 00:16:23.720 align:middle line:84%
We're going to solve today a
particular case of it, which

00:16:23.720 --> 00:16:26.545 align:middle line:90%
is suppose you have six people.

00:16:26.545 --> 00:16:29.360 align:middle line:90%


00:16:29.360 --> 00:16:33.820 align:middle line:84%
And every two of them are
either friends or not.

00:16:33.820 --> 00:16:45.170 align:middle line:90%


00:16:45.170 --> 00:16:48.290 align:middle line:84%
And this is an exclusive or,
so I'm going to write XOR.

00:16:48.290 --> 00:16:52.160 align:middle line:84%
You're allowed to be friends
or not friends, not both,

00:16:52.160 --> 00:16:53.798 align:middle line:90%
and not neither.

00:16:53.798 --> 00:16:55.340 align:middle line:84%
And in the not
friends case, I'm also

00:16:55.340 --> 00:16:58.580 align:middle line:90%
going to call them strangers.

00:16:58.580 --> 00:17:00.630 align:middle line:84%
So this is like
extreme friendship.

00:17:00.630 --> 00:17:02.960 align:middle line:84%
Either you declare
yourself as friends

00:17:02.960 --> 00:17:05.338 align:middle line:84%
or as knowing each other, or
you don't know each other.

00:17:05.338 --> 00:17:06.630 align:middle line:90%
In that case, you're strangers.

00:17:06.630 --> 00:17:09.650 align:middle line:84%
You're just never both, and
it's always one or the other.

00:17:09.650 --> 00:17:11.480 align:middle line:84%
So you can think
of this as I can

00:17:11.480 --> 00:17:14.569 align:middle line:84%
draw a little picture of there
are six people represented

00:17:14.569 --> 00:17:15.240 align:middle line:90%
by circles.

00:17:15.240 --> 00:17:17.310 align:middle line:84%
You can put smiley faces
in them if you want.

00:17:17.310 --> 00:17:20.300 align:middle line:84%
And maybe I connect
them via a white line

00:17:20.300 --> 00:17:25.310 align:middle line:84%
if they are friends and a dotted
line if they're strangers.

00:17:25.310 --> 00:17:29.890 align:middle line:84%
So let's-- and every two of them
have one of these two pictures.

00:17:29.890 --> 00:17:32.990 align:middle line:90%


00:17:32.990 --> 00:17:35.600 align:middle line:90%
Probably missing some.

00:17:35.600 --> 00:17:38.210 align:middle line:90%
Here.

00:17:38.210 --> 00:17:41.030 align:middle line:90%
OK, that's them all.

00:17:41.030 --> 00:17:51.388 align:middle line:84%
Then I claim no matter
what the situation is,

00:17:51.388 --> 00:17:53.430 align:middle line:84%
which ones are friends,
which ones are strangers,

00:17:53.430 --> 00:18:09.890 align:middle line:84%
there's always either three
mutual friends or three

00:18:09.890 --> 00:18:11.136 align:middle line:90%
mutual strangers.

00:18:11.136 --> 00:18:17.200 align:middle line:90%


00:18:17.200 --> 00:18:17.700 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:18:17.700 --> 00:18:20.970 align:middle line:84%
In this example--
hopefully I drew enough.

00:18:20.970 --> 00:18:23.000 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:27.360 align:middle line:84%
These three people
are mutual strangers.

00:18:27.360 --> 00:18:32.190 align:middle line:84%
They're connected by a
triangle of dashed lines, OK?

00:18:32.190 --> 00:18:35.540 align:middle line:84%
If I drew some other pattern, if
they were all solid lines, then

00:18:35.540 --> 00:18:39.000 align:middle line:84%
I might get the other situation,
at least three mutual friends.

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:40.980 align:middle line:84%
But it turns out, if
you have six people,

00:18:40.980 --> 00:18:43.160 align:middle line:84%
they're always at least
three mutual friends

00:18:43.160 --> 00:18:45.000 align:middle line:90%
or three mutual strangers.

00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:47.050 align:middle line:90%
Let's prove this by cases.

00:18:47.050 --> 00:18:57.980 align:middle line:90%


00:18:57.980 --> 00:19:00.660 align:middle line:84%
Whenever we apply
a proof by cases,

00:19:00.660 --> 00:19:04.700 align:middle line:84%
we need to come up with
some proposition C that's

00:19:04.700 --> 00:19:07.670 align:middle line:84%
either true or false, well,
for a proof by two cases, which

00:19:07.670 --> 00:19:08.335 align:middle line:90%
this will be.

00:19:08.335 --> 00:19:11.630 align:middle line:90%


00:19:11.630 --> 00:19:14.490 align:middle line:84%
And it's a little work
in this case to do it.

00:19:14.490 --> 00:19:21.860 align:middle line:84%
It turns out a useful first
step is to pick any person P. So

00:19:21.860 --> 00:19:24.320 align:middle line:84%
just take the first
person or the seventh--

00:19:24.320 --> 00:19:27.020 align:middle line:90%
or the fifth person out of six.

00:19:27.020 --> 00:19:29.430 align:middle line:84%
Doesn't matter which
one, but label it P.

00:19:29.430 --> 00:19:31.590 align:middle line:84%
So now we have a
person to talk about.

00:19:31.590 --> 00:19:36.380 align:middle line:84%
This is like the proof by
example or by construction,

00:19:36.380 --> 00:19:37.280 align:middle line:90%
right?

00:19:37.280 --> 00:19:39.157 align:middle line:84%
Overall there, we want
to prove an existence.

00:19:39.157 --> 00:19:41.240 align:middle line:84%
We want to prove existence
of three mutual friends

00:19:41.240 --> 00:19:43.350 align:middle line:84%
or existence of three
mutual strangers.

00:19:43.350 --> 00:19:46.560 align:middle line:84%
So that's a useful step
to either construct one.

00:19:46.560 --> 00:19:49.260 align:middle line:84%
Or in this case, we're actually
not doing much for construction.

00:19:49.260 --> 00:19:51.060 align:middle line:84%
We're just taking
an arbitrary x.

00:19:51.060 --> 00:19:55.190 align:middle line:84%
But that will be enough
for this problem.

00:19:55.190 --> 00:20:00.740 align:middle line:84%
So let me draw a
little circle for P.

00:20:00.740 --> 00:20:03.170 align:middle line:84%
And it might have
some friends, and it

00:20:03.170 --> 00:20:05.040 align:middle line:90%
might have some strangers.

00:20:05.040 --> 00:20:05.540 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:20:05.540 --> 00:20:08.000 align:middle line:84%
How many of these lines
coming out of P are there?

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:11.420 align:middle line:84%
Five exactly because there
are six people total.

00:20:11.420 --> 00:20:12.660 align:middle line:90%
P is one of them.

00:20:12.660 --> 00:20:15.930 align:middle line:84%
So there are five
people over here, OK?

00:20:15.930 --> 00:20:21.020 align:middle line:84%
So turns out useful
case strategy is

00:20:21.020 --> 00:20:28.790 align:middle line:84%
to say either P has at
least three friends,

00:20:28.790 --> 00:20:31.710 align:middle line:84%
or it has less than
three friends, right?

00:20:31.710 --> 00:20:34.490 align:middle line:84%
Either there are three solid
lines, like I've drawn here,

00:20:34.490 --> 00:20:36.120 align:middle line:90%
or there are at least three--

00:20:36.120 --> 00:20:39.340 align:middle line:84%
or there are at most
two solid lines.

00:20:39.340 --> 00:20:39.840 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:20:39.840 --> 00:20:41.257 align:middle line:84%
Let's think about
this first case.

00:20:41.257 --> 00:20:43.320 align:middle line:90%
P has at least three friends.

00:20:43.320 --> 00:20:52.160 align:middle line:84%
Let's give them a name,
Q, R, and S. So that's

00:20:52.160 --> 00:20:53.190 align:middle line:90%
a general picture.

00:20:53.190 --> 00:20:58.625 align:middle line:84%
Now we're assuming P has three
solid lines to three people

00:20:58.625 --> 00:21:03.030 align:middle line:90%
Q, R, and S. OK.

00:21:03.030 --> 00:21:04.440 align:middle line:90%
This is not yet a triangle.

00:21:04.440 --> 00:21:06.650 align:middle line:84%
We haven't solved
the problem yet.

00:21:06.650 --> 00:21:11.810 align:middle line:84%
But if we break into more
cases we'll be able to.

00:21:11.810 --> 00:21:25.890 align:middle line:84%
So case 1A is going to be some
two of Q, R, and S are friends.

00:21:25.890 --> 00:21:28.480 align:middle line:90%


00:21:28.480 --> 00:21:35.050 align:middle line:84%
Suppose, for example,
Q and S are friends.

00:21:35.050 --> 00:21:36.290 align:middle line:90%
Have I found a triangle?

00:21:36.290 --> 00:21:42.530 align:middle line:84%
Yes, P, Q, and S are mutual
friends if this edge is here.

00:21:42.530 --> 00:21:44.950 align:middle line:84%
Or if this edge is here,
then these three people

00:21:44.950 --> 00:21:46.460 align:middle line:90%
are three mutual friends.

00:21:46.460 --> 00:21:49.310 align:middle line:84%
Or if this edge is here, these
three people or mutual friends.

00:21:49.310 --> 00:21:51.490 align:middle line:84%
If there's any edge in
here that I can draw,

00:21:51.490 --> 00:21:56.500 align:middle line:84%
any solid line between Q, R, and
S, then those two people plus P

00:21:56.500 --> 00:21:59.440 align:middle line:90%
form three mutual friends.

00:21:59.440 --> 00:22:02.170 align:middle line:90%
So that case is actually easy.

00:22:02.170 --> 00:22:03.520 align:middle line:90%
Great.

00:22:03.520 --> 00:22:17.990 align:middle line:84%
Then P plus those two people
are three mutual friends, OK,

00:22:17.990 --> 00:22:21.120 align:middle line:90%
which was situation one up here.

00:22:21.120 --> 00:22:22.870 align:middle line:84%
There's always either
three mutual friends

00:22:22.870 --> 00:22:26.620 align:middle line:90%
or three mutual strangers.

00:22:26.620 --> 00:22:27.820 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:22:27.820 --> 00:22:30.640 align:middle line:84%
So now we need to think
about the other cases.

00:22:30.640 --> 00:22:32.410 align:middle line:90%
Let's go over here.

00:22:32.410 --> 00:22:37.550 align:middle line:84%
We found one case that was
easy, but there's case 1B,

00:22:37.550 --> 00:22:39.650 align:middle line:84%
which is maybe there
aren't two mutual friends.

00:22:39.650 --> 00:22:41.920 align:middle line:84%
And there's case
two, where P does not

00:22:41.920 --> 00:22:43.960 align:middle line:90%
have at least three friends.

00:22:43.960 --> 00:22:46.810 align:middle line:84%
But it turns out all of
these cases will be easy.

00:22:46.810 --> 00:22:52.120 align:middle line:90%
So let's do case 1B.

00:22:52.120 --> 00:22:55.220 align:middle line:84%
Now, I get to freely
choose what case 1 was,

00:22:55.220 --> 00:22:57.910 align:middle line:84%
and I get to freely choose what
case 1A was because whenever I

00:22:57.910 --> 00:23:00.430 align:middle line:84%
split into cases, I get to
choose my proposition C to be

00:23:00.430 --> 00:23:01.520 align:middle line:90%
anything I want.

00:23:01.520 --> 00:23:03.260 align:middle line:90%
So this was C in the first case.

00:23:03.260 --> 00:23:04.820 align:middle line:90%
This was C in the second case.

00:23:04.820 --> 00:23:07.640 align:middle line:84%
But generally, if you're
doing proof by two cases,

00:23:07.640 --> 00:23:09.410 align:middle line:84%
you have no choice
at this point.

00:23:09.410 --> 00:23:11.330 align:middle line:90%
So case 1A was whatever.

00:23:11.330 --> 00:23:15.430 align:middle line:84%
Case 1B has to be
the negation of this.

00:23:15.430 --> 00:23:23.470 align:middle line:84%
So case 1B literally is not
some 2 of Q, R, S are friends.

00:23:23.470 --> 00:23:25.390 align:middle line:84%
But if you think about
that for a little bit

00:23:25.390 --> 00:23:33.760 align:middle line:90%
this is saying Q, R, and S--

00:23:33.760 --> 00:23:37.910 align:middle line:84%
let me write this in
a couple of steps.

00:23:37.910 --> 00:23:43.410 align:middle line:84%
No two of Q, R,
and S are friends.

00:23:43.410 --> 00:23:48.430 align:middle line:90%


00:23:48.430 --> 00:23:50.470 align:middle line:84%
But that's the same
thing as saying Q, R,

00:23:50.470 --> 00:23:52.906 align:middle line:90%
and S are mutual strangers.

00:23:52.906 --> 00:24:01.850 align:middle line:90%


00:24:01.850 --> 00:24:02.350 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:24:02.350 --> 00:24:05.020 align:middle line:84%
We're using this fact,
or this assumption,

00:24:05.020 --> 00:24:10.960 align:middle line:84%
that every two people are either
friends or strangers, always one

00:24:10.960 --> 00:24:11.660 align:middle line:90%
or the other.

00:24:11.660 --> 00:24:15.610 align:middle line:84%
So if there's no solid line
over here, then all of these

00:24:15.610 --> 00:24:18.020 align:middle line:90%
are dashed lines.

00:24:18.020 --> 00:24:19.970 align:middle line:84%
So all three of these
are mutual strangers.

00:24:19.970 --> 00:24:24.250 align:middle line:84%
And there we found our
triangle of strangers, OK?

00:24:24.250 --> 00:24:27.710 align:middle line:84%
So it turns out case 1A and case
1B are actually just as easy

00:24:27.710 --> 00:24:29.380 align:middle line:90%
just reversed.

00:24:29.380 --> 00:24:33.370 align:middle line:90%
So this was situation two.

00:24:33.370 --> 00:24:35.230 align:middle line:84%
So either we got
three mutual friends,

00:24:35.230 --> 00:24:36.950 align:middle line:84%
or we got three
mutual strangers.

00:24:36.950 --> 00:24:38.530 align:middle line:90%
But we're still inside case 1.

00:24:38.530 --> 00:24:40.210 align:middle line:90%
We just finished case 1.

00:24:40.210 --> 00:24:42.230 align:middle line:84%
Now we need to
think about case 2.

00:24:42.230 --> 00:24:47.020 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to unindent
here and go to case 2.

00:24:47.020 --> 00:24:49.970 align:middle line:84%
Case 2, again, has to be
exactly the opposite of this.

00:24:49.970 --> 00:24:54.610 align:middle line:84%
So P does not have at
least three friends.

00:24:54.610 --> 00:24:58.160 align:middle line:84%
By number of people
being an integer,

00:24:58.160 --> 00:25:04.630 align:middle line:84%
this is saying P has
at most two friends.

00:25:04.630 --> 00:25:07.000 align:middle line:84%
If it doesn't have at
least three, it's at most 2

00:25:07.000 --> 00:25:11.140 align:middle line:84%
because the number of
friends is always an integer.

00:25:11.140 --> 00:25:12.050 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:25:12.050 --> 00:25:12.560 align:middle line:90%
Great.

00:25:12.560 --> 00:25:16.570 align:middle line:84%
So case 2 is a
negation of case 1.

00:25:16.570 --> 00:25:19.090 align:middle line:84%
And it turns out
that is also kind of

00:25:19.090 --> 00:25:21.970 align:middle line:90%
easy for asymmetric reason.

00:25:21.970 --> 00:25:24.560 align:middle line:84%
Remember, there are
six people total.

00:25:24.560 --> 00:25:28.540 align:middle line:90%
So there's P and five others.

00:25:28.540 --> 00:25:36.670 align:middle line:90%
So how many strangers is P with?

00:25:36.670 --> 00:25:40.870 align:middle line:84%
How many people is
P a stranger to?

00:25:40.870 --> 00:25:46.803 align:middle line:84%
Well, it's at least all
the others, 5 minus 2.

00:25:46.803 --> 00:25:48.470 align:middle line:84%
Because at most two
of them are friends.

00:25:48.470 --> 00:25:50.650 align:middle line:84%
The remainder have
to be strangers.

00:25:50.650 --> 00:25:53.828 align:middle line:90%
And so this is 3.

00:25:53.828 --> 00:25:55.870 align:middle line:84%
So P having at most two
friends is the same thing

00:25:55.870 --> 00:25:58.130 align:middle line:84%
as P having at least
three strangers

00:25:58.130 --> 00:26:01.510 align:middle line:84%
because there are five
other people total.

00:26:01.510 --> 00:26:03.910 align:middle line:90%
2 plus 3 is 5.

00:26:03.910 --> 00:26:07.560 align:middle line:84%
So case 2 is P has at
least three strangers.

00:26:07.560 --> 00:26:10.300 align:middle line:84%
Case 1 was P has at
least three friends.

00:26:10.300 --> 00:26:11.720 align:middle line:90%
These are almost the same.

00:26:11.720 --> 00:26:15.280 align:middle line:84%
I just have to flip
friends versus strangers.

00:26:15.280 --> 00:26:17.260 align:middle line:84%
So the way I would
write this in a proof

00:26:17.260 --> 00:26:32.950 align:middle line:84%
is this is symmetric
to case 1 swapping

00:26:32.950 --> 00:26:35.516 align:middle line:90%
friends versus strangers.

00:26:35.516 --> 00:26:39.880 align:middle line:90%


00:26:39.880 --> 00:26:46.030 align:middle line:84%
And of course, situation
1 with situation 2.

00:26:46.030 --> 00:26:49.870 align:middle line:84%
So case 2 would be P has at
least three strangers, Q, R,

00:26:49.870 --> 00:26:54.470 align:middle line:84%
and S. Case 1A is that some two
of Q, R, and S are strangers.

00:26:54.470 --> 00:26:56.800 align:middle line:84%
Then we conclude
that P plus those two

00:26:56.800 --> 00:27:00.760 align:middle line:84%
are three mutual strangers,
which is situation 2.

00:27:00.760 --> 00:27:05.920 align:middle line:84%
Or case 2B would be no two
of Q, R, S are strangers.

00:27:05.920 --> 00:27:08.520 align:middle line:84%
In other words., Q, R,
S are mutual friends.

00:27:08.520 --> 00:27:10.510 align:middle line:90%
And then we're in situation 1.

00:27:10.510 --> 00:27:13.493 align:middle line:84%
So case 2 works just like case 1
just swapping the words friends

00:27:13.493 --> 00:27:15.910 align:middle line:84%
and strangers because they
didn't really have any meaning.

00:27:15.910 --> 00:27:18.690 align:middle line:90%
They were just words.

00:27:18.690 --> 00:27:19.650 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:27:19.650 --> 00:27:25.360 align:middle line:84%
So in all cases, we
prove the desired result.

00:27:25.360 --> 00:27:28.320 align:middle line:84%
Either situation 1 or
situation 2 happens.

00:27:28.320 --> 00:27:31.565 align:middle line:84%
This is a particular case of
something called Ramsey Theory.

00:27:31.565 --> 00:27:37.200 align:middle line:90%


00:27:37.200 --> 00:27:41.692 align:middle line:84%
What we've just found is
that something called R of 3,

00:27:41.692 --> 00:27:46.530 align:middle line:90%
3 is at most 6.

00:27:46.530 --> 00:27:50.850 align:middle line:84%
In general, R of f
comma S is the number

00:27:50.850 --> 00:27:54.270 align:middle line:84%
of people you need
in order to guarantee

00:27:54.270 --> 00:27:58.480 align:middle line:84%
that there's at least f friends
or at least S strangers.

00:27:58.480 --> 00:28:00.133 align:middle line:84%
So we just did at
least three friends

00:28:00.133 --> 00:28:01.300 align:middle line:90%
or at least three strangers.

00:28:01.300 --> 00:28:03.100 align:middle line:84%
We showed that six
people was enough.

00:28:03.100 --> 00:28:06.400 align:middle line:84%
It turns out six people is
exactly the right number.

00:28:06.400 --> 00:28:09.600 align:middle line:84%
You need six people in order to
guarantee at least three friends

00:28:09.600 --> 00:28:11.140 align:middle line:90%
or three strangers.

00:28:11.140 --> 00:28:16.120 align:middle line:84%
If you wanted to guarantee
four friends or four strangers,

00:28:16.120 --> 00:28:19.235 align:middle line:90%
turns out you need 18 people.

00:28:19.235 --> 00:28:21.840 align:middle line:90%


00:28:21.840 --> 00:28:25.330 align:middle line:84%
If you want to guarantee five
friends or five strangers,

00:28:25.330 --> 00:28:32.500 align:middle line:84%
turns out you need somewhere
between 43 and 48 people.

00:28:32.500 --> 00:28:34.240 align:middle line:90%
But we don't know how many.

00:28:34.240 --> 00:28:36.243 align:middle line:84%
So while this problem
was relatively easy,

00:28:36.243 --> 00:28:38.160 align:middle line:84%
three friends or three
strangers, five friends

00:28:38.160 --> 00:28:41.980 align:middle line:84%
and five strangers already is an
unsolved mathematical problem.

00:28:41.980 --> 00:28:44.640 align:middle line:84%
So that's kind of cool
and crazy how easily you

00:28:44.640 --> 00:28:47.255 align:middle line:90%
get to very difficult problems.

00:28:47.255 --> 00:28:49.630 align:middle line:84%
Of course, people will try to
compute larger numbers too,

00:28:49.630 --> 00:28:54.360 align:middle line:84%
but we don't have tight
bounds, generally.

00:28:54.360 --> 00:28:55.090 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:28:55.090 --> 00:28:56.820 align:middle line:84%
I want to say one
more thing about proof

00:28:56.820 --> 00:29:00.365 align:middle line:84%
by cases, which is what if
we want more than two cases?

00:29:00.365 --> 00:29:03.510 align:middle line:90%


00:29:03.510 --> 00:29:09.827 align:middle line:84%
So more generally,
proof by k cases.

00:29:09.827 --> 00:29:19.800 align:middle line:90%


00:29:19.800 --> 00:29:22.560 align:middle line:84%
So instead of just C
or not C, let's suppose

00:29:22.560 --> 00:29:25.470 align:middle line:84%
we have a bunch of
propositions, C1 through Ck.

00:29:25.470 --> 00:29:30.661 align:middle line:84%
And let's suppose that
this is a tautology,

00:29:30.661 --> 00:29:32.710 align:middle line:90%
my favorite word for the day.

00:29:32.710 --> 00:29:36.820 align:middle line:84%
So suppose that it's always the
case, C1 or C2 or dot, dot, dot,

00:29:36.820 --> 00:29:37.570 align:middle line:90%
or Ck.

00:29:37.570 --> 00:29:40.260 align:middle line:84%
One of these things
is always true.

00:29:40.260 --> 00:29:48.330 align:middle line:84%
Then we can follow
this template which

00:29:48.330 --> 00:29:53.070 align:middle line:84%
is suppose we want to prove a
theorem that some proposition

00:29:53.070 --> 00:29:57.150 align:middle line:90%
P is true.

00:29:57.150 --> 00:30:06.080 align:middle line:84%
Then we'll say a proof by
cases, and there's k of them.

00:30:06.080 --> 00:30:07.830 align:middle line:84%
So I'm just going to
write it generically.

00:30:07.830 --> 00:30:12.820 align:middle line:90%
In case i, is that Ci is true.

00:30:12.820 --> 00:30:17.700 align:middle line:84%
In other words, we get
to assume Ci is true.

00:30:17.700 --> 00:30:20.430 align:middle line:84%
And then what we need
to do is prove that P

00:30:20.430 --> 00:30:22.200 align:middle line:90%
is true in that scenario.

00:30:22.200 --> 00:30:26.623 align:middle line:90%
And P is true because reasons.

00:30:26.623 --> 00:30:29.820 align:middle line:90%


00:30:29.820 --> 00:30:31.650 align:middle line:84%
And then here it's
especially important

00:30:31.650 --> 00:30:45.460 align:middle line:84%
to say that the cases are
exhaustive because reasons.

00:30:45.460 --> 00:30:51.450 align:middle line:84%
And exhaustive here just means
that C1 or C2 or up to Ck

00:30:51.450 --> 00:30:53.056 align:middle line:90%
is a tautology.

00:30:53.056 --> 00:30:56.160 align:middle line:90%


00:30:56.160 --> 00:30:59.860 align:middle line:84%
So you need to
prove that C1 or--

00:30:59.860 --> 00:31:02.628 align:middle line:84%
dot, dot, dot, or
Ck is always true.

00:31:02.628 --> 00:31:04.670 align:middle line:84%
That's the meaning of the
cases being exhaustive.

00:31:04.670 --> 00:31:05.750 align:middle line:90%
So there's two parts.

00:31:05.750 --> 00:31:07.490 align:middle line:84%
One is to prove that
each case is OK.

00:31:07.490 --> 00:31:11.440 align:middle line:84%
The other is to prove that
those cases cover everything.

00:31:11.440 --> 00:31:14.870 align:middle line:84%
So I won't show an
example of k cases here.

00:31:14.870 --> 00:31:17.210 align:middle line:84%
We'll see them in
recitation, and so on.

00:31:17.210 --> 00:31:21.860 align:middle line:84%
But I will tell you a story
about one famous proof by cases,

00:31:21.860 --> 00:31:25.240 align:middle line:90%
which is the Four Color Theorem.

00:31:25.240 --> 00:31:28.430 align:middle line:84%
I'll illustrate the Four
Color Theorem with an example.

00:31:28.430 --> 00:31:32.050 align:middle line:84%
So here's a map of
the United States.

00:31:32.050 --> 00:31:34.870 align:middle line:84%
And I've colored all the
states, all the regions

00:31:34.870 --> 00:31:37.150 align:middle line:84%
of this map with four
different colors,

00:31:37.150 --> 00:31:39.910 align:middle line:84%
red, green, blue,
yellow, in such a way

00:31:39.910 --> 00:31:43.690 align:middle line:84%
that if you have two
regions that share

00:31:43.690 --> 00:31:48.010 align:middle line:84%
a positive length boundary,
then this color A is

00:31:48.010 --> 00:31:53.312 align:middle line:84%
different from this color
B. It has to be not equal.

00:31:53.312 --> 00:31:55.645 align:middle line:84%
Otherwise, if you had two red
regions next to each other

00:31:55.645 --> 00:31:57.187 align:middle line:84%
it would be hard to
see the boundary.

00:31:57.187 --> 00:31:59.140 align:middle line:84%
So the colors illustrate
the boundaries

00:31:59.140 --> 00:32:01.130 align:middle line:90%
between all the regions.

00:32:01.130 --> 00:32:04.630 align:middle line:84%
Four colors seems to
be enough for this map.

00:32:04.630 --> 00:32:09.070 align:middle line:84%
It's also enough for this
map of all the countries.

00:32:09.070 --> 00:32:11.000 align:middle line:90%
Is it true for all the maps?

00:32:11.000 --> 00:32:12.387 align:middle line:90%
Turns out, yes, this is called--

00:32:12.387 --> 00:32:14.720 align:middle line:84%
for a long time it was called
the Four Color Conjecture.

00:32:14.720 --> 00:32:18.280 align:middle line:84%
And then it became the Four
Color Theorem at some date.

00:32:18.280 --> 00:32:19.810 align:middle line:84%
So Four Color
Theorem says you can

00:32:19.810 --> 00:32:22.398 align:middle line:84%
color the regions of any
planar map with four colors

00:32:22.398 --> 00:32:24.440 align:middle line:84%
so that neighboring regions
get different colors.

00:32:24.440 --> 00:32:30.340 align:middle line:84%
This was first observed
and conjectured in 1852

00:32:30.340 --> 00:32:34.030 align:middle line:84%
by a guy named Guthrie, who
was a student of De Morgan.

00:32:34.030 --> 00:32:38.240 align:middle line:84%
De Morgan, I think, his name
will come up in a moment,

00:32:38.240 --> 00:32:39.530 align:middle line:90%
famous logician.

00:32:39.530 --> 00:32:43.750 align:middle line:84%
He actually invented
induction as we--

00:32:43.750 --> 00:32:45.670 align:middle line:84%
one of the first
people to-- he invented

00:32:45.670 --> 00:32:47.900 align:middle line:84%
the term mathematical
induction, at the very least,

00:32:47.900 --> 00:32:51.670 align:middle line:90%
and really made it more formal.

00:32:51.670 --> 00:32:53.532 align:middle line:84%
So a student of him,
Guthrie, said, hey,

00:32:53.532 --> 00:32:54.990 align:middle line:84%
I took all the
counties of England.

00:32:54.990 --> 00:32:57.310 align:middle line:84%
And it turned out I
only needed four colors.

00:32:57.310 --> 00:32:58.390 align:middle line:90%
Is this a theorem?

00:32:58.390 --> 00:33:00.990 align:middle line:84%
And he asked
indirectly De Morgan.

00:33:00.990 --> 00:33:02.560 align:middle line:84%
And De Morgan said,
hey, seems cool.

00:33:02.560 --> 00:33:03.900 align:middle line:90%
I don't know, maybe.

00:33:03.900 --> 00:33:08.490 align:middle line:84%
Then the following year,
1853, another mathematician

00:33:08.490 --> 00:33:15.690 align:middle line:90%
named Kempe proves the theorem.

00:33:15.690 --> 00:33:20.130 align:middle line:84%
But proved should be in
quotes because 11 years

00:33:20.130 --> 00:33:23.980 align:middle line:84%
later, 1864, Heawood
found a bug in that proof.

00:33:23.980 --> 00:33:26.290 align:middle line:84%
Turns out there were a lot
of cases in this proof,

00:33:26.290 --> 00:33:28.300 align:middle line:84%
and the cases were
not exhaustive.

00:33:28.300 --> 00:33:30.360 align:middle line:90%
So it wasn't done.

00:33:30.360 --> 00:33:36.940 align:middle line:84%
Then, 15 years later, 1880,
Tait proved the theorem.

00:33:36.940 --> 00:33:40.660 align:middle line:84%
Then 11 years later, Petersen
found a bug in that proof.

00:33:40.660 --> 00:33:42.790 align:middle line:84%
Again, not all the
cases were exhaustive.

00:33:42.790 --> 00:33:50.647 align:middle line:84%
Then, 85 years later,
1976, Appel and Haken--

00:33:50.647 --> 00:33:52.105 align:middle line:84%
or maybe it's Appel,
I'm not sure--

00:33:52.105 --> 00:33:56.930 align:middle line:90%


00:33:56.930 --> 00:33:58.170 align:middle line:90%
proved the theorem.

00:33:58.170 --> 00:34:01.040 align:middle line:84%
And I think most people
consider this an actual proof.

00:34:01.040 --> 00:34:02.400 align:middle line:90%
But it's a little tricky.

00:34:02.400 --> 00:34:05.220 align:middle line:84%
Just to give you a
sense, this is where my--

00:34:05.220 --> 00:34:06.720 align:middle line:84%
I started hearing
about the problem.

00:34:06.720 --> 00:34:10.250 align:middle line:84%
I wasn't alive in 1976, but
I heard about it later on.

00:34:10.250 --> 00:34:14.010 align:middle line:84%
There are 1,834
cases in this proof.

00:34:14.010 --> 00:34:17.510 align:middle line:84%
They occupy about a 400-page
printout from a computer

00:34:17.510 --> 00:34:18.270 align:middle line:90%
program.

00:34:18.270 --> 00:34:21.409 align:middle line:84%
And so this is one of the
first mathematical proofs

00:34:21.409 --> 00:34:24.870 align:middle line:84%
that used a computer to assist
in checking all the cases.

00:34:24.870 --> 00:34:29.300 align:middle line:84%
Because there's so many, 1,834,
it's hard to do that by hand

00:34:29.300 --> 00:34:31.530 align:middle line:84%
and be sure that you
didn't make a mistake.

00:34:31.530 --> 00:34:35.929 align:middle line:84%
So the computer proof, to me,
is a little bit more sound.

00:34:35.929 --> 00:34:40.940 align:middle line:84%
Also apparently checked by
hand by Haken's daughter.

00:34:40.940 --> 00:34:45.199 align:middle line:84%
Then, five years
later, Schmidt found

00:34:45.199 --> 00:34:47.670 align:middle line:84%
what you could interpret
as a bug in this proof,

00:34:47.670 --> 00:34:49.610 align:middle line:84%
let's say an omission
or something,

00:34:49.610 --> 00:34:51.590 align:middle line:90%
but a missing situation.

00:34:51.590 --> 00:34:53.400 align:middle line:84%
And then over the
next eight years,

00:34:53.400 --> 00:34:56.130 align:middle line:84%
Appel and Haken fixed all
the bugs they could find,

00:34:56.130 --> 00:34:59.190 align:middle line:84%
that one and some other
wording issues, and so on.

00:34:59.190 --> 00:35:01.970 align:middle line:84%
And then they
published it in a book.

00:35:01.970 --> 00:35:05.630 align:middle line:84%
But a book isn't refereed, so I
don't know how many people have

00:35:05.630 --> 00:35:07.310 align:middle line:90%
read that book.

00:35:07.310 --> 00:35:09.450 align:middle line:84%
It seems like this
proof is maybe correct.

00:35:09.450 --> 00:35:12.740 align:middle line:84%
It's been many years, and
no one has found a bug.

00:35:12.740 --> 00:35:15.600 align:middle line:84%
A little bit later,
though, in 1996,

00:35:15.600 --> 00:35:17.700 align:middle line:84%
Robertson, Sanders,
Seymour, and Thomas,

00:35:17.700 --> 00:35:21.170 align:middle line:84%
some of the top graph
theorists in the world,

00:35:21.170 --> 00:35:22.760 align:middle line:90%
found a simpler proof.

00:35:22.760 --> 00:35:25.800 align:middle line:90%
That proof only has 633 cases.

00:35:25.800 --> 00:35:29.130 align:middle line:84%
So that's a lot less, maybe
three times fewer cases.

00:35:29.130 --> 00:35:30.920 align:middle line:84%
And also, the
length of the paper

00:35:30.920 --> 00:35:33.200 align:middle line:84%
is shorter, maybe
10 times shorter.

00:35:33.200 --> 00:35:34.710 align:middle line:90%
So that's progress.

00:35:34.710 --> 00:35:36.060 align:middle line:90%
But is that proof true?

00:35:36.060 --> 00:35:38.480 align:middle line:84%
It also used a computer
to check the cases.

00:35:38.480 --> 00:35:44.360 align:middle line:84%
Finally, in 2005,
Werner and Gonthier

00:35:44.360 --> 00:35:49.220 align:middle line:84%
developed a fully
computer-checkable proof using

00:35:49.220 --> 00:35:53.600 align:middle line:84%
a system called Coq,
where you write down

00:35:53.600 --> 00:35:54.930 align:middle line:90%
every step in the proof.

00:35:54.930 --> 00:35:57.050 align:middle line:84%
And then the computer
just has to check

00:35:57.050 --> 00:36:01.400 align:middle line:84%
that every mathematical
derivation, all the derivations

00:36:01.400 --> 00:36:03.830 align:middle line:84%
we saw last class, modus
ponens, and all those things,

00:36:03.830 --> 00:36:04.920 align:middle line:90%
are correct.

00:36:04.920 --> 00:36:10.830 align:middle line:84%
This program has withstood
many, many years of scrutiny.

00:36:10.830 --> 00:36:12.330 align:middle line:84%
So we all believe
that it's correct.

00:36:12.330 --> 00:36:14.455 align:middle line:84%
And so the fact that you
can write the entire proof

00:36:14.455 --> 00:36:16.730 align:middle line:84%
in this proof language
suggests that this really is

00:36:16.730 --> 00:36:18.900 align:middle line:90%
a true theorem now, thankfully.

00:36:18.900 --> 00:36:21.680 align:middle line:84%
There won't be
more missing cases.

00:36:21.680 --> 00:36:24.440 align:middle line:84%
I believe that is just an
implementation of the Robertson

00:36:24.440 --> 00:36:25.050 align:middle line:90%
proof.

00:36:25.050 --> 00:36:28.707 align:middle line:90%
So that one withstood scrutiny.

00:36:28.707 --> 00:36:30.540 align:middle line:84%
But it's very tedious
to write these proofs.

00:36:30.540 --> 00:36:34.010 align:middle line:84%
And so for the Four Color
Theorem, it's worth it,

00:36:34.010 --> 00:36:35.510 align:middle line:90%
I would say.

00:36:35.510 --> 00:36:38.000 align:middle line:84%
All right, so that's just
an example of, in general,

00:36:38.000 --> 00:36:40.503 align:middle line:84%
proofs by cases can
involve a zillion cases.

00:36:40.503 --> 00:36:42.170 align:middle line:84%
It's very annoying,
but sometimes that's

00:36:42.170 --> 00:36:43.560 align:middle line:84%
the best thing we
know how to do.

00:36:43.560 --> 00:36:46.018 align:middle line:84%
Maybe we'll come up with a
simpler Four Color Theorem proof

00:36:46.018 --> 00:36:51.360 align:middle line:84%
at some point, but best we know
so far has hundreds of cases.

00:36:51.360 --> 00:36:56.550 align:middle line:84%
All right, let's go
back to induction.

00:36:56.550 --> 00:36:59.010 align:middle line:84%
At first I want to review
induction a little bit,

00:36:59.010 --> 00:37:03.500 align:middle line:84%
and then we will get
a stronger form of it.

00:37:03.500 --> 00:37:09.660 align:middle line:90%


00:37:09.660 --> 00:37:14.850 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to call
this the induction axiom.

00:37:14.850 --> 00:37:18.960 align:middle line:84%
This is what we talked
about last class.

00:37:18.960 --> 00:37:20.680 align:middle line:90%
We didn't call it an axiom.

00:37:20.680 --> 00:37:22.153 align:middle line:84%
And in some setups
it is an axiom.

00:37:22.153 --> 00:37:23.820 align:middle line:84%
We're going to take
it as one, something

00:37:23.820 --> 00:37:26.580 align:middle line:90%
that we just assume is true.

00:37:26.580 --> 00:37:28.900 align:middle line:84%
Although, as Zach
mentioned, in modern times,

00:37:28.900 --> 00:37:31.050 align:middle line:84%
you usually prove
this using other--

00:37:31.050 --> 00:37:35.058 align:middle line:84%
using the definition
of the natural numbers.

00:37:35.058 --> 00:37:36.850 align:middle line:84%
But I'll just take it
as something is true.

00:37:36.850 --> 00:37:40.300 align:middle line:84%
So for any predicate P of
n over the natural numbers,

00:37:40.300 --> 00:37:50.000 align:middle line:84%
if on the one hand P of 0 is
true and on the other hand,

00:37:50.000 --> 00:37:59.120 align:middle line:84%
P of n implies P of n plus
1 for all natural numbers n,

00:37:59.120 --> 00:38:07.820 align:middle line:84%
then P of n is true for
all natural numbers n.

00:38:07.820 --> 00:38:10.565 align:middle line:90%
This is the magic of induction.

00:38:10.565 --> 00:38:12.440 align:middle line:84%
You should use this
probably in every problem

00:38:12.440 --> 00:38:15.900 align:middle line:84%
you solve, not every problem,
but extremely powerful tool.

00:38:15.900 --> 00:38:18.350 align:middle line:84%
We're going to use it all the
time throughout this class.

00:38:18.350 --> 00:38:20.870 align:middle line:84%
I want to give you a
visual way of thinking

00:38:20.870 --> 00:38:22.910 align:middle line:84%
about what's going on
with induction, which

00:38:22.910 --> 00:38:24.063 align:middle line:90%
I call block diagrams.

00:38:24.063 --> 00:38:31.730 align:middle line:90%


00:38:31.730 --> 00:38:40.940 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to
think of a block,

00:38:40.940 --> 00:38:44.880 align:middle line:84%
like a little box here,
that takes as input--

00:38:44.880 --> 00:38:46.500 align:middle line:90%
think of it as a procedure.

00:38:46.500 --> 00:38:51.690 align:middle line:84%
You give it some true
propositions on the left,

00:38:51.690 --> 00:38:55.795 align:middle line:84%
and it produces a true
proposition on the right.

00:38:55.795 --> 00:38:58.480 align:middle line:90%


00:38:58.480 --> 00:38:58.980 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:38:58.980 --> 00:39:00.647 align:middle line:84%
Or we could think of
it as if I give you

00:39:00.647 --> 00:39:02.550 align:middle line:84%
some proofs of
these propositions,

00:39:02.550 --> 00:39:05.360 align:middle line:84%
then this block will
give you a proof

00:39:05.360 --> 00:39:07.640 align:middle line:90%
of a proposition on the right.

00:39:07.640 --> 00:39:11.180 align:middle line:84%
So what's going
on with induction

00:39:11.180 --> 00:39:15.380 align:middle line:84%
is we're given two of
these blocks, these two.

00:39:15.380 --> 00:39:18.440 align:middle line:84%
So you can think of
part 1, P of 0 is true,

00:39:18.440 --> 00:39:21.360 align:middle line:90%
as a block that has no input.

00:39:21.360 --> 00:39:24.930 align:middle line:84%
So this is what we normally
call the base case.

00:39:24.930 --> 00:39:26.850 align:middle line:84%
So it doesn't need
to assume anything.

00:39:26.850 --> 00:39:31.580 align:middle line:84%
And it just produces for you
a proof that P of 0 is true.

00:39:31.580 --> 00:39:36.890 align:middle line:84%
And the second part
here, the induction step,

00:39:36.890 --> 00:39:40.510 align:middle line:84%
says that if you can
prove P of n is true

00:39:40.510 --> 00:39:43.870 align:middle line:84%
and you plug it into
the induction step,

00:39:43.870 --> 00:39:48.140 align:middle line:84%
then it will give you a proof
that P of n plus 1 is true.

00:39:48.140 --> 00:39:50.180 align:middle line:84%
Saw a bunch of examples
of this last time.

00:39:50.180 --> 00:39:56.140 align:middle line:84%
We assume P of n, and we use
that to prove P of n plus 1, OK?

00:39:56.140 --> 00:39:58.990 align:middle line:84%
Now, the cool thing about
blocks is you can just

00:39:58.990 --> 00:40:00.850 align:middle line:90%
chain them together.

00:40:00.850 --> 00:40:06.070 align:middle line:84%
So if we chain, the only
block we can place first

00:40:06.070 --> 00:40:09.100 align:middle line:84%
is this base case because
it doesn't need anything

00:40:09.100 --> 00:40:10.130 align:middle line:90%
to get started.

00:40:10.130 --> 00:40:13.510 align:middle line:84%
So we start with the
base case argument.

00:40:13.510 --> 00:40:15.490 align:middle line:90%
That produces P of 0.

00:40:15.490 --> 00:40:17.600 align:middle line:90%
Now we plug this into the step.

00:40:17.600 --> 00:40:21.670 align:middle line:90%
This step has to work for all n.

00:40:21.670 --> 00:40:24.350 align:middle line:84%
So in particular, it
works for n equals 0.

00:40:24.350 --> 00:40:30.010 align:middle line:84%
And so we plug that into the
step, and we get a P of 1.

00:40:30.010 --> 00:40:34.240 align:middle line:84%
We plug P of 1 into the
step, so n equals 1.

00:40:34.240 --> 00:40:38.230 align:middle line:84%
Then we get P of n
plus 1, namely, P of 2.

00:40:38.230 --> 00:40:44.560 align:middle line:84%
And we plug that into the step,
and we get P of 3, and so on.

00:40:44.560 --> 00:40:46.120 align:middle line:84%
So this just gives
you some intuition

00:40:46.120 --> 00:40:48.830 align:middle line:84%
for if I can build an argument
for why P of 0 is true

00:40:48.830 --> 00:40:51.490 align:middle line:84%
and I can build an
argument for why if P of n

00:40:51.490 --> 00:40:54.080 align:middle line:84%
is true, then P of n
plus 1 is also true,

00:40:54.080 --> 00:40:56.320 align:middle line:84%
then I can just repeat
that argument over

00:40:56.320 --> 00:40:59.030 align:middle line:84%
and over with different n,
increasing n by 1 each time.

00:40:59.030 --> 00:41:02.540 align:middle line:84%
And I can use that to prove that
all the P of n's are true, OK?

00:41:02.540 --> 00:41:06.397 align:middle line:84%
This is visual intuition
for why this works.

00:41:06.397 --> 00:41:08.230 align:middle line:84%
Of course, we're not
going to actually prove

00:41:08.230 --> 00:41:11.470 align:middle line:84%
P of n is true for
all n, but should

00:41:11.470 --> 00:41:13.890 align:middle line:90%
be pretty intuitive from that.

00:41:13.890 --> 00:41:16.810 align:middle line:90%


00:41:16.810 --> 00:41:27.370 align:middle line:84%
Or more abstractly, you can
actually think of induction

00:41:27.370 --> 00:41:30.760 align:middle line:90%
itself as one of these blocks.

00:41:30.760 --> 00:41:32.055 align:middle line:90%
Let me use another color.

00:41:32.055 --> 00:41:36.700 align:middle line:90%


00:41:36.700 --> 00:41:42.160 align:middle line:84%
So we have, on the
one hand a block base

00:41:42.160 --> 00:41:43.970 align:middle line:90%
which produces P of 0.

00:41:43.970 --> 00:41:47.890 align:middle line:84%
And we have an induction
step, which given P of n,

00:41:47.890 --> 00:41:53.500 align:middle line:90%
produces P of n plus 1.

00:41:53.500 --> 00:41:58.510 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to think of
this as a thing that's true

00:41:58.510 --> 00:42:00.470 align:middle line:90%
and this as a thing that's true.

00:42:00.470 --> 00:42:03.250 align:middle line:84%
And then what
induction gives me,

00:42:03.250 --> 00:42:08.360 align:middle line:84%
induction is a block that,
given these two facts--

00:42:08.360 --> 00:42:10.430 align:middle line:84%
if you can prove
each of these things,

00:42:10.430 --> 00:42:17.380 align:middle line:84%
then it gives me a new fact,
which is for all natural numbers

00:42:17.380 --> 00:42:19.785 align:middle line:90%
n, P of n is true.

00:42:19.785 --> 00:42:22.480 align:middle line:90%


00:42:22.480 --> 00:42:24.790 align:middle line:84%
So that's the--
instead of having

00:42:24.790 --> 00:42:27.830 align:middle line:84%
to draw out this
infinite length path,

00:42:27.830 --> 00:42:29.630 align:middle line:84%
induction just does
it all at once.

00:42:29.630 --> 00:42:32.540 align:middle line:84%
It says, oh, I know I can chain
these all together forever.

00:42:32.540 --> 00:42:35.290 align:middle line:84%
Therefore P of n is
true for all n, OK?

00:42:35.290 --> 00:42:39.610 align:middle line:84%
I don't know if that helps,
but it's another visual way

00:42:39.610 --> 00:42:41.060 align:middle line:90%
of thinking about induction.

00:42:41.060 --> 00:42:45.230 align:middle line:90%


00:42:45.230 --> 00:42:45.730 align:middle line:90%
Let's--

00:42:45.730 --> 00:42:54.520 align:middle line:90%


00:42:54.520 --> 00:43:00.430 align:middle line:84%
All right, let me tell you
another equivalent formulation

00:43:00.430 --> 00:43:01.943 align:middle line:90%
of induction, which I prefer.

00:43:01.943 --> 00:43:11.560 align:middle line:90%


00:43:11.560 --> 00:43:12.920 align:middle line:90%
It starts out the same.

00:43:12.920 --> 00:43:14.550 align:middle line:90%
Suppose P of 0 is true.

00:43:14.550 --> 00:43:16.960 align:middle line:90%


00:43:16.960 --> 00:43:19.460 align:middle line:84%
The induction step I'm going
to phrase slightly differently,

00:43:19.460 --> 00:43:20.530 align:middle line:90%
almost the same.

00:43:20.530 --> 00:43:27.600 align:middle line:84%
For all n at least one P of
n minus 1 implies P of n.

00:43:27.600 --> 00:43:30.250 align:middle line:90%


00:43:30.250 --> 00:43:37.660 align:middle line:84%
Then, for all natural
numbers, P of n.

00:43:37.660 --> 00:43:40.910 align:middle line:84%
So the first and last
lines are the same.

00:43:40.910 --> 00:43:42.455 align:middle line:90%
We assume P of 0 is true.

00:43:42.455 --> 00:43:45.080 align:middle line:84%
We're going to conclude P of n
is true for all natural numbers.

00:43:45.080 --> 00:43:49.150 align:middle line:84%
Here we started at 0, and we
wanted to show that P of n

00:43:49.150 --> 00:43:50.710 align:middle line:90%
implies P of n plus 1.

00:43:50.710 --> 00:43:53.530 align:middle line:84%
Over here, we're
starting at 1 and we're

00:43:53.530 --> 00:43:55.813 align:middle line:84%
proving that P of n
minus 1 implies P of n.

00:43:55.813 --> 00:43:57.230 align:middle line:84%
These are exactly
the same things.

00:43:57.230 --> 00:43:59.210 align:middle line:84%
I've just shifted
the indices by one.

00:43:59.210 --> 00:44:02.230 align:middle line:84%
So these are
identical statements,

00:44:02.230 --> 00:44:04.390 align:middle line:90%
or equivalent statements.

00:44:04.390 --> 00:44:05.950 align:middle line:90%
I like this version.

00:44:05.950 --> 00:44:08.672 align:middle line:84%
In particular, it will
lead into strong induction.

00:44:08.672 --> 00:44:10.630 align:middle line:84%
But I like this version
as a computer scientist

00:44:10.630 --> 00:44:13.090 align:middle line:84%
because I always want to think
about-- what I want to prove

00:44:13.090 --> 00:44:16.100 align:middle line:90%
P of n, not P of n plus 1.

00:44:16.100 --> 00:44:18.380 align:middle line:84%
It's confusing to think
about proving P of n plus 1.

00:44:18.380 --> 00:44:19.870 align:middle line:90%
I always want to prove P of n.

00:44:19.870 --> 00:44:22.340 align:middle line:84%
When n equals 0, OK,
that's my base case.

00:44:22.340 --> 00:44:23.530 align:middle line:90%
I proved that specially.

00:44:23.530 --> 00:44:26.540 align:middle line:84%
When n is at least 1,
I'm not in the base case,

00:44:26.540 --> 00:44:30.190 align:middle line:84%
and I get to assume that
P of n minus 1 is true.

00:44:30.190 --> 00:44:32.150 align:middle line:84%
You can think of this
like a computer program.

00:44:32.150 --> 00:44:36.040 align:middle line:84%
Think of a-- proving P of n
is like running a computation

00:44:36.040 --> 00:44:37.840 align:middle line:90%
f of n, or P of n.

00:44:37.840 --> 00:44:41.350 align:middle line:84%
And I get to recursively
call P of n minus 1

00:44:41.350 --> 00:44:43.417 align:middle line:84%
in order to compute P
of n. n is given to me.

00:44:43.417 --> 00:44:44.750 align:middle line:90%
This is the one I want to solve.

00:44:44.750 --> 00:44:47.180 align:middle line:84%
If n is 0, then I
solve it one way.

00:44:47.180 --> 00:44:49.700 align:middle line:84%
If n is bigger than
0 or at least 1,

00:44:49.700 --> 00:44:53.440 align:middle line:84%
then I recursively call P of n
minus 1 or depend on that proof

00:44:53.440 --> 00:44:55.540 align:middle line:90%
and use it to prove P of n.

00:44:55.540 --> 00:44:57.400 align:middle line:84%
But you can use
either one, whichever

00:44:57.400 --> 00:44:58.995 align:middle line:90%
is more comfortable to you.

00:44:58.995 --> 00:45:02.200 align:middle line:90%


00:45:02.200 --> 00:45:03.830 align:middle line:84%
But really, you
should use neither,

00:45:03.830 --> 00:45:07.250 align:middle line:84%
and you should use this stronger
form called strong induction.

00:45:07.250 --> 00:45:09.090 align:middle line:90%
So let's do that.

00:45:09.090 --> 00:45:18.820 align:middle line:90%


00:45:18.820 --> 00:45:21.330 align:middle line:84%
Strong induction just gives
you more to work with.

00:45:21.330 --> 00:45:36.180 align:middle line:90%


00:45:36.180 --> 00:45:38.430 align:middle line:84%
So it's in some
sense more powerful.

00:45:38.430 --> 00:45:40.270 align:middle line:84%
Logically, it's
identical to induction.

00:45:40.270 --> 00:45:43.890 align:middle line:84%
You can actually prove it using
induction, and we'll do that.

00:45:43.890 --> 00:45:45.460 align:middle line:90%
Let me first state the theorem.

00:45:45.460 --> 00:46:01.660 align:middle line:84%
So if for any natural
number this is true,

00:46:01.660 --> 00:46:11.370 align:middle line:84%
then for any natural
number P of n is true, OK?

00:46:11.370 --> 00:46:13.700 align:middle line:84%
Let me bring this
one down to compare.

00:46:13.700 --> 00:46:18.270 align:middle line:90%


00:46:18.270 --> 00:46:20.347 align:middle line:84%
So first thing
maybe to notice is

00:46:20.347 --> 00:46:21.930 align:middle line:84%
that it doesn't seem
to be a base case

00:46:21.930 --> 00:46:23.860 align:middle line:90%
here, which is a little weird.

00:46:23.860 --> 00:46:25.870 align:middle line:84%
It's just one
condition then this.

00:46:25.870 --> 00:46:29.430 align:middle line:84%
Let's compare the
steps, first of all.

00:46:29.430 --> 00:46:33.070 align:middle line:84%
Or I guess let's
think about the case--

00:46:33.070 --> 00:46:34.540 align:middle line:90%
this has to be true for all n.

00:46:34.540 --> 00:46:37.560 align:middle line:84%
If we think about when n equals
0, that's the missing base

00:46:37.560 --> 00:46:44.100 align:middle line:84%
case, what this is actually
saying is P0 up to P minus 1

00:46:44.100 --> 00:46:46.800 align:middle line:90%
implies P of 0.

00:46:46.800 --> 00:46:48.700 align:middle line:84%
So this is kind
of weird notation.

00:46:48.700 --> 00:46:51.160 align:middle line:84%
I'm abusing the dot, dot,
dot a little bit here.

00:46:51.160 --> 00:46:54.940 align:middle line:84%
And for when n equals
1, this is P of 0.

00:46:54.940 --> 00:46:57.580 align:middle line:84%
When n equals 2, this
is P of 0 and P of 1.

00:46:57.580 --> 00:47:00.615 align:middle line:84%
When n equals 3, for larger n
it's very clear what this dot,

00:47:00.615 --> 00:47:01.240 align:middle line:90%
dot, dot means.

00:47:01.240 --> 00:47:03.310 align:middle line:84%
But when n equals
0 it's confusing.

00:47:03.310 --> 00:47:05.310 align:middle line:90%
So I need to specify.

00:47:05.310 --> 00:47:12.078 align:middle line:84%
This is defined to be
true for n equals 0, OK?

00:47:12.078 --> 00:47:13.620 align:middle line:84%
So for n equals 0
what you have to do

00:47:13.620 --> 00:47:17.730 align:middle line:84%
is prove that true
implies P of 0.

00:47:17.730 --> 00:47:21.370 align:middle line:84%
In other words, P of 0 must
be true in all cases, OK?

00:47:21.370 --> 00:47:25.060 align:middle line:84%
So there's-- but
then for larger n,

00:47:25.060 --> 00:47:28.170 align:middle line:84%
what this is saying is not only
do I get to assume P of n minus

00:47:28.170 --> 00:47:33.870 align:middle line:84%
1, but I get to assume all
the P of i's before P of n.

00:47:33.870 --> 00:47:39.490 align:middle line:84%
So I would normally say P of i
is true for all i less than n.

00:47:39.490 --> 00:47:42.330 align:middle line:90%
This is what I get to assume.

00:47:42.330 --> 00:47:48.150 align:middle line:84%
That's probably actually a
better way to state this thing.

00:47:48.150 --> 00:47:50.370 align:middle line:84%
So with regular
induction here, I

00:47:50.370 --> 00:47:53.110 align:middle line:84%
got to assume that the previous
P of n minus 1 was true,

00:47:53.110 --> 00:47:55.900 align:middle line:84%
and I needed to use that to
prove that P of n is true.

00:47:55.900 --> 00:47:58.320 align:middle line:84%
But actually, if you
look at this chain,

00:47:58.320 --> 00:48:01.020 align:middle line:84%
by the time I'm proving P of
3, I've already proved all

00:48:01.020 --> 00:48:03.120 align:middle line:90%
the smaller Pi's.

00:48:03.120 --> 00:48:04.440 align:middle line:90%
So why not assume that.

00:48:04.440 --> 00:48:06.273 align:middle line:84%
With strong induction,
I get to assume that.

00:48:06.273 --> 00:48:08.220 align:middle line:84%
In order to prove P
of n, I get to assume

00:48:08.220 --> 00:48:12.150 align:middle line:84%
all the Pi's where
i is less than n.

00:48:12.150 --> 00:48:14.430 align:middle line:84%
Now, when n equals 0, I
don't get to assume anything

00:48:14.430 --> 00:48:17.190 align:middle line:84%
because there are
no smaller i's.

00:48:17.190 --> 00:48:23.610 align:middle line:84%
But when I get to P of 5, I get
to assume P0, P1, P2, P3, P4.

00:48:23.610 --> 00:48:26.450 align:middle line:84%
So I get to assume more, so
this only makes my proof easier.

00:48:26.450 --> 00:48:29.490 align:middle line:90%


00:48:29.490 --> 00:48:31.800 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:48:31.800 --> 00:48:35.830 align:middle line:84%
To be clear, this is
usually proved in cases.

00:48:35.830 --> 00:48:39.847 align:middle line:84%
Normally, you need
to check 0 specially.

00:48:39.847 --> 00:48:40.930 align:middle line:90%
That might be a base case.

00:48:40.930 --> 00:48:42.520 align:middle line:84%
Maybe you have to
check 1 specially.

00:48:42.520 --> 00:48:46.470 align:middle line:84%
It depends on your
implication argument.

00:48:46.470 --> 00:48:49.940 align:middle line:84%
Often, this implication assumes
that n is at least something,

00:48:49.940 --> 00:48:51.690 align:middle line:84%
and then you have to
prove all the smaller

00:48:51.690 --> 00:48:53.530 align:middle line:90%
n's to be true specially.

00:48:53.530 --> 00:48:55.690 align:middle line:84%
But we'll get to
examples in a moment.

00:48:55.690 --> 00:48:57.870 align:middle line:84%
What I'd like to do
first is actually

00:48:57.870 --> 00:48:59.945 align:middle line:84%
prove that strong
induction is true.

00:48:59.945 --> 00:49:02.507 align:middle line:90%


00:49:02.507 --> 00:49:04.840 align:middle line:84%
This is not something you
would repeat in your homework.

00:49:04.840 --> 00:49:06.840 align:middle line:84%
You should just assume
strong induction is true.

00:49:06.840 --> 00:49:09.510 align:middle line:84%
But I think it's
instructive to see

00:49:09.510 --> 00:49:15.420 align:middle line:84%
why it's true as yet another
example of induction.

00:49:15.420 --> 00:49:18.630 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to use regular
induction, this version,

00:49:18.630 --> 00:49:21.900 align:middle line:84%
or actually, I think this
version, the induction axiom,

00:49:21.900 --> 00:49:25.870 align:middle line:90%
to prove strong induction, OK?

00:49:25.870 --> 00:49:27.600 align:middle line:84%
Now, this is a
situation where we

00:49:27.600 --> 00:49:31.530 align:middle line:84%
need to define a particular
induction hypothesis that's

00:49:31.530 --> 00:49:35.100 align:middle line:90%
not the obvious one.

00:49:35.100 --> 00:49:36.910 align:middle line:90%
And this is not at all obvious.

00:49:36.910 --> 00:49:44.760 align:middle line:84%
But I'm going to define
ih of n to be this P of 0

00:49:44.760 --> 00:49:49.170 align:middle line:90%
and P of n minus 1.

00:49:49.170 --> 00:49:53.910 align:middle line:84%
In other words, for all
i less than n, P of i.

00:49:53.910 --> 00:49:56.220 align:middle line:84%
I like that better
because it works even when

00:49:56.220 --> 00:49:59.140 align:middle line:84%
n is 0 because there
are no i's less than 0.

00:49:59.140 --> 00:50:02.460 align:middle line:90%
So that's just true when n is 0.

00:50:02.460 --> 00:50:06.180 align:middle line:84%
So this is the thing I
want to prove for all n.

00:50:06.180 --> 00:50:07.270 align:middle line:90%
And how do we do it?

00:50:07.270 --> 00:50:13.230 align:middle line:84%
Well, as usual, with an
induction, we have a base case.

00:50:13.230 --> 00:50:17.490 align:middle line:90%
Base case is ih of 0.

00:50:17.490 --> 00:50:23.520 align:middle line:84%
So ih of 0 is actually
literally just true

00:50:23.520 --> 00:50:25.090 align:middle line:84%
because we defined
it to be that way.

00:50:25.090 --> 00:50:28.600 align:middle line:84%
We say when n equals 0,
this dot, dot, dot is true.

00:50:28.600 --> 00:50:29.580 align:middle line:90%
Or you could say--

00:50:29.580 --> 00:50:32.010 align:middle line:84%
this is saying for
all i less than 0,

00:50:32.010 --> 00:50:34.380 align:middle line:90%
where i is a natural number.

00:50:34.380 --> 00:50:37.120 align:middle line:84%
But there are no natural
numbers less than 0,

00:50:37.120 --> 00:50:39.190 align:middle line:84%
so this is like saying
if false, then something.

00:50:39.190 --> 00:50:40.650 align:middle line:90%
And that's just always true.

00:50:40.650 --> 00:50:46.930 align:middle line:84%
So this is, by definition,
ih of 0 is true.

00:50:46.930 --> 00:50:48.150 align:middle line:90%
Great?

00:50:48.150 --> 00:50:51.960 align:middle line:90%
Easy base case as usual.

00:50:51.960 --> 00:50:54.310 align:middle line:84%
What's the induction
step look like?

00:50:54.310 --> 00:50:56.040 align:middle line:90%
I'm going to--

00:50:56.040 --> 00:50:57.070 align:middle line:90%
I get to choose.

00:50:57.070 --> 00:51:01.300 align:middle line:84%
I could either assume ih of n
minus 1 and prove of ih of n.

00:51:01.300 --> 00:51:09.820 align:middle line:84%
Or I'm going to assume if of
n and prove ih of n plus 1.

00:51:09.820 --> 00:51:12.905 align:middle line:84%
So we want to show ih of n
plus 1, assuming ih of n.

00:51:12.905 --> 00:51:15.560 align:middle line:90%


00:51:15.560 --> 00:51:16.910 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:51:16.910 --> 00:51:19.980 align:middle line:84%
So the key thing is we get
to assume this is true.

00:51:19.980 --> 00:51:22.200 align:middle line:84%
The strong induction
says if this, then this.

00:51:22.200 --> 00:51:23.640 align:middle line:90%
So we're assuming the if part.

00:51:23.640 --> 00:51:28.140 align:middle line:84%
We're assuming that
if this implication.

00:51:28.140 --> 00:51:34.130 align:middle line:84%
And this thing here
is exactly ih of n.

00:51:34.130 --> 00:51:37.760 align:middle line:84%
So this says ih of
n implies P of n.

00:51:37.760 --> 00:51:44.270 align:middle line:84%
So we know ih of
n implies P of n.

00:51:44.270 --> 00:51:48.830 align:middle line:84%
That's what we get to assume
in our theorem statement here.

00:51:48.830 --> 00:51:51.530 align:middle line:84%
And we just assumed
that ih of n is true.

00:51:51.530 --> 00:51:55.670 align:middle line:90%
Therefore, P of n is true.

00:51:55.670 --> 00:51:57.900 align:middle line:84%
But P of n was not what
we wanted to prove.

00:51:57.900 --> 00:51:59.880 align:middle line:84%
We wanted to prove
ih of n plus 1.

00:51:59.880 --> 00:52:01.705 align:middle line:90%
So what is ih of n plus 1?

00:52:01.705 --> 00:52:05.000 align:middle line:90%


00:52:05.000 --> 00:52:07.490 align:middle line:84%
Let's just expand out
this definition here.

00:52:07.490 --> 00:52:14.630 align:middle line:84%
It is P of 0 or dot, dot,
dot, or P of n minus 1

00:52:14.630 --> 00:52:18.600 align:middle line:84%
or P of n because of
incremented n by 1.

00:52:18.600 --> 00:52:20.280 align:middle line:84%
This no longer ends
at P of n minus 1.

00:52:20.280 --> 00:52:22.490 align:middle line:90%
It now ends at P of n.

00:52:22.490 --> 00:52:24.090 align:middle line:84%
But this is almost
what we had before.

00:52:24.090 --> 00:52:26.850 align:middle line:84%
This is the induction
hypothesis of n.

00:52:26.850 --> 00:52:33.560 align:middle line:90%
That's this part, or P of n.

00:52:33.560 --> 00:52:36.800 align:middle line:84%
That's just a
formula manipulation.

00:52:36.800 --> 00:52:40.460 align:middle line:84%
And this we assumed is
true, ih of n is true.

00:52:40.460 --> 00:52:43.490 align:middle line:84%
And P of n we just
proved is true.

00:52:43.490 --> 00:52:44.210 align:middle line:90%
Sorry.

00:52:44.210 --> 00:52:47.570 align:middle line:84%
I wrote over here, but
I meant and everywhere.

00:52:47.570 --> 00:52:50.990 align:middle line:90%
This is and, and.

00:52:50.990 --> 00:52:51.660 align:middle line:90%
See?

00:52:51.660 --> 00:52:55.710 align:middle line:84%
Even professors get the
V's and wedges upside down.

00:52:55.710 --> 00:52:57.330 align:middle line:90%
So I wrote it correctly here.

00:52:57.330 --> 00:52:59.400 align:middle line:84%
It's the and of P0
up to Pn minus 1.

00:52:59.400 --> 00:53:02.510 align:middle line:84%
Here we have the
and of P0 up to Pn.

00:53:02.510 --> 00:53:06.020 align:middle line:84%
And so this is ih of n, which we
assumed was true by induction,

00:53:06.020 --> 00:53:10.920 align:middle line:84%
and P of n, which we just
proved using one induction step.

00:53:10.920 --> 00:53:13.225 align:middle line:90%
Therefore, the and is also true.

00:53:13.225 --> 00:53:17.210 align:middle line:90%


00:53:17.210 --> 00:53:20.490 align:middle line:84%
And I believe that's the
end of the proof, all right?

00:53:20.490 --> 00:53:21.300 align:middle line:90%
I did a base case.

00:53:21.300 --> 00:53:22.050 align:middle line:90%
I did a step.

00:53:22.050 --> 00:53:23.460 align:middle line:90%
Oh, no, not quite the answer.

00:53:23.460 --> 00:53:24.080 align:middle line:90%
Sorry.

00:53:24.080 --> 00:53:29.770 align:middle line:84%
There's one more step here,
which I will put over here.

00:53:29.770 --> 00:53:34.340 align:middle line:90%


00:53:34.340 --> 00:53:37.880 align:middle line:84%
This is a good illustration
in not skipping steps.

00:53:37.880 --> 00:53:39.650 align:middle line:90%
What did we actually prove?

00:53:39.650 --> 00:53:42.860 align:middle line:84%
By induction, we proved
induction hypothesis of n

00:53:42.860 --> 00:53:45.440 align:middle line:90%
is true for all n.

00:53:45.440 --> 00:53:56.150 align:middle line:84%
So by induction, the
regular old induction axiom,

00:53:56.150 --> 00:54:02.060 align:middle line:84%
for all natural numbers n,
induction hypothesis of n

00:54:02.060 --> 00:54:04.573 align:middle line:90%
is true.

00:54:04.573 --> 00:54:06.240 align:middle line:84%
Induction hypothesis
of n is this thing.

00:54:06.240 --> 00:54:07.865 align:middle line:84%
But that's not what
we wanted to prove.

00:54:07.865 --> 00:54:12.380 align:middle line:84%
We wanted to prove P of
n is true for all of n.

00:54:12.380 --> 00:54:15.930 align:middle line:84%
But I can do some manipulation
to make that what I want.

00:54:15.930 --> 00:54:23.340 align:middle line:84%
So this is like saying
for all n, let's see.

00:54:23.340 --> 00:54:24.950 align:middle line:84%
Actually, probably
this is nicer.

00:54:24.950 --> 00:54:32.030 align:middle line:84%
For all natural numbers,
ih of n plus 1 is true, OK?

00:54:32.030 --> 00:54:33.060 align:middle line:90%
This is a shift.

00:54:33.060 --> 00:54:34.320 align:middle line:90%
It's actually a weaker shift.

00:54:34.320 --> 00:54:36.180 align:middle line:90%
This includes ih of 0.

00:54:36.180 --> 00:54:39.030 align:middle line:84%
This should not be
greater than or equal to.

00:54:39.030 --> 00:54:40.970 align:middle line:90%
This should be an element of.

00:54:40.970 --> 00:54:42.240 align:middle line:90%
This includes 0.

00:54:42.240 --> 00:54:42.890 align:middle line:90%
This doesn't.

00:54:42.890 --> 00:54:45.240 align:middle line:84%
This starts at 1,
and it goes upwards.

00:54:45.240 --> 00:54:46.970 align:middle line:90%
But this is nice.

00:54:46.970 --> 00:54:50.300 align:middle line:90%
So this implies this, right?

00:54:50.300 --> 00:54:51.382 align:middle line:90%
This is what we've shown.

00:54:51.382 --> 00:54:53.090 align:middle line:84%
This is a weaker
statement because I just

00:54:53.090 --> 00:54:56.615 align:middle line:84%
threw away ih of 0. ih of 0
wasn't interesting anyway.

00:54:56.615 --> 00:55:01.970 align:middle line:84%
ih of 1 includes
inside of it-- so it's

00:55:01.970 --> 00:55:04.350 align:middle line:90%
an and of a bunch of things.

00:55:04.350 --> 00:55:06.545 align:middle line:84%
But then the last
term is P of n.

00:55:06.545 --> 00:55:09.050 align:middle line:90%


00:55:09.050 --> 00:55:13.670 align:middle line:84%
If I take ih of n plus 1, the
last term in it is P of n.

00:55:13.670 --> 00:55:18.750 align:middle line:84%
So it's also anded,
but if the and is true,

00:55:18.750 --> 00:55:20.370 align:middle line:90%
then every term is true.

00:55:20.370 --> 00:55:24.740 align:middle line:84%
And so, therefore, P
of n is true for all n.

00:55:24.740 --> 00:55:26.160 align:middle line:90%
So this is a final cleanup.

00:55:26.160 --> 00:55:27.927 align:middle line:84%
After we did induction,
we didn't quite

00:55:27.927 --> 00:55:29.510 align:middle line:84%
get the statement
we wanted because we

00:55:29.510 --> 00:55:33.110 align:middle line:84%
used a different induction
hypothesis than just P.

00:55:33.110 --> 00:55:37.520 align:middle line:84%
And then we needed to show
that implied P of n for all n.

00:55:37.520 --> 00:55:40.380 align:middle line:90%
But it works.

00:55:40.380 --> 00:55:40.880 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:55:40.880 --> 00:55:43.160 align:middle line:84%
So now there should
be no question

00:55:43.160 --> 00:55:45.960 align:middle line:84%
about why strong
induction is true,

00:55:45.960 --> 00:55:48.530 align:middle line:90%
assuming you believe this proof.

00:55:48.530 --> 00:55:51.440 align:middle line:90%
You can draw a diagram.

00:55:51.440 --> 00:55:54.300 align:middle line:90%
It's a little trickier to do.

00:55:54.300 --> 00:55:59.463 align:middle line:84%
Maybe I will show you in
my handwritten notes here.

00:55:59.463 --> 00:56:03.260 align:middle line:90%


00:56:03.260 --> 00:56:08.930 align:middle line:84%
Here is a block diagram
for strong induction.

00:56:08.930 --> 00:56:12.210 align:middle line:84%
It's harder to draw because
you depend on so many things.

00:56:12.210 --> 00:56:14.850 align:middle line:84%
When I apply the
fourth step here,

00:56:14.850 --> 00:56:19.680 align:middle line:84%
when I want to conclude P of 4,
I assume all the previous P's.

00:56:19.680 --> 00:56:23.870 align:middle line:84%
So P0, P1, P2, P3, they
all feed into this box.

00:56:23.870 --> 00:56:25.470 align:middle line:84%
In the beginning,
it's very similar.

00:56:25.470 --> 00:56:27.720 align:middle line:90%
I apply a step, I get P of 0.

00:56:27.720 --> 00:56:29.700 align:middle line:84%
Then I apply that
P of 0 to a step.

00:56:29.700 --> 00:56:31.460 align:middle line:90%
I get P of 1.

00:56:31.460 --> 00:56:35.660 align:middle line:84%
But then, as I proceed,
I'm feeding more and more

00:56:35.660 --> 00:56:39.345 align:middle line:84%
Pi's into the step, and it
gives me one more Pi, OK?

00:56:39.345 --> 00:56:40.970 align:middle line:84%
So it's a much more
complicated diagram

00:56:40.970 --> 00:56:43.230 align:middle line:84%
of what's going
on under the hood,

00:56:43.230 --> 00:56:47.060 align:middle line:84%
but from a usage standpoint,
it only helps you.

00:56:47.060 --> 00:56:48.780 align:middle line:84%
When you're trying
to prove P of n,

00:56:48.780 --> 00:56:51.090 align:middle line:84%
you don't just get to
assume P of n minus 1.

00:56:51.090 --> 00:56:57.110 align:middle line:84%
You get to assume all the
Pi's where i is less than n.

00:56:57.110 --> 00:57:00.440 align:middle line:84%
I forgot one part of the Four
Color Theorem story, which

00:57:00.440 --> 00:57:04.610 align:middle line:84%
was when I was growing up, I
read a reprint of this article

00:57:04.610 --> 00:57:06.080 align:middle line:84%
by Martin Gardner,
which turned out

00:57:06.080 --> 00:57:07.700 align:middle line:84%
to be published on
April Fools, but I

00:57:07.700 --> 00:57:09.440 align:middle line:90%
didn't know it at the time.

00:57:09.440 --> 00:57:15.710 align:middle line:84%
And in 1975, there was no proof
of the Four Color Theorem.

00:57:15.710 --> 00:57:18.290 align:middle line:84%
Appel and Haken
was one year later.

00:57:18.290 --> 00:57:22.020 align:middle line:84%
So at this point he published
a joke saying, in fact,

00:57:22.020 --> 00:57:24.840 align:middle line:84%
McGregor found this map,
which requires five colors.

00:57:24.840 --> 00:57:28.580 align:middle line:84%
I remember sitting there trying
to color it with four colors

00:57:28.580 --> 00:57:29.520 align:middle line:90%
and always failing.

00:57:29.520 --> 00:57:30.690 align:middle line:90%
I was like, oh, my gosh.

00:57:30.690 --> 00:57:32.090 align:middle line:90%
Four Color Theorem isn't true.

00:57:32.090 --> 00:57:34.860 align:middle line:84%
Or Four Color Conjecture, as
it was called then, isn't true.

00:57:34.860 --> 00:57:35.970 align:middle line:90%
Isn't that amazing?

00:57:35.970 --> 00:57:37.080 align:middle line:90%
But it was all a lie.

00:57:37.080 --> 00:57:39.260 align:middle line:84%
In fact, you can
four-color that map.

00:57:39.260 --> 00:57:41.670 align:middle line:84%
But it's a very funny article
if you want to read it.

00:57:41.670 --> 00:57:44.750 align:middle line:84%
It's in the lecture notes,
or part of it is there.

00:57:44.750 --> 00:57:49.490 align:middle line:84%
All sorts of crazy things like,
oh, it turns out, if you take e

00:57:49.490 --> 00:57:52.680 align:middle line:84%
and you raise it to pi
times square root of 163,

00:57:52.680 --> 00:57:54.420 align:middle line:90%
the result is an integer.

00:57:54.420 --> 00:57:55.850 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

00:57:55.850 --> 00:57:58.190 align:middle line:84%
It's not true, but all
sorts of crazy things.

00:57:58.190 --> 00:58:01.320 align:middle line:84%
Also, chess has a
crazy winning move.

00:58:01.320 --> 00:58:06.650 align:middle line:84%
And-- anyway, let's
relive the youth.

00:58:06.650 --> 00:58:14.050 align:middle line:84%
All right, I think
I'd like to, yeah,

00:58:14.050 --> 00:58:16.760 align:middle line:84%
show you some examples
of strong induction.

00:58:16.760 --> 00:58:19.720 align:middle line:84%
But maybe first I should
show you a template

00:58:19.720 --> 00:58:22.850 align:middle line:84%
for applying induction,
strong induction.

00:58:22.850 --> 00:58:26.892 align:middle line:90%


00:58:26.892 --> 00:58:28.850 align:middle line:84%
We'll repeat some of the
things that I've said,

00:58:28.850 --> 00:58:33.040 align:middle line:84%
but I think it's good
to have it concrete.

00:58:33.040 --> 00:58:34.903 align:middle line:90%
So here is a template.

00:58:34.903 --> 00:58:37.810 align:middle line:90%


00:58:37.810 --> 00:58:41.350 align:middle line:84%
Suppose you want
to prove something

00:58:41.350 --> 00:58:43.310 align:middle line:90%
is true for all natural numbers.

00:58:43.310 --> 00:58:48.790 align:middle line:84%
So for all natural
numbers n, P of n is true.

00:58:48.790 --> 00:58:54.320 align:middle line:84%
Then here's what the proof
will look like by proof

00:58:54.320 --> 00:58:55.326 align:middle line:90%
by strong induction.

00:58:55.326 --> 00:59:05.320 align:middle line:90%


00:59:05.320 --> 00:59:11.920 align:middle line:84%
So generally, we're assuming
P of k for all k less than n.

00:59:11.920 --> 00:59:17.307 align:middle line:90%
And then we want to show P of n.

00:59:17.307 --> 00:59:18.890 align:middle line:84%
Or you could shift
the numbers by one,

00:59:18.890 --> 00:59:22.060 align:middle line:84%
but this is my preferred
way of thinking about it.

00:59:22.060 --> 00:59:28.160 align:middle line:84%
Usually, we prove this by cases,
which is the method we just saw.

00:59:28.160 --> 00:59:31.280 align:middle line:84%
This is why we're pairing proof
by cases with strong induction.

00:59:31.280 --> 00:59:32.900 align:middle line:90%
How do we prove P of n?

00:59:32.900 --> 00:59:34.580 align:middle line:90%
Well, it might depend.

00:59:34.580 --> 00:59:41.080 align:middle line:84%
Often, we have some base
cases where n is small.

00:59:41.080 --> 00:59:43.880 align:middle line:84%
So maybe we have
to prove P of 0.

00:59:43.880 --> 00:59:46.480 align:middle line:90%
Maybe we have to prove P of 1.

00:59:46.480 --> 00:59:47.770 align:middle line:90%
Who knows?

00:59:47.770 --> 00:59:52.070 align:middle line:84%
Let's say up to P of little
b are the base cases.

00:59:52.070 --> 00:59:55.900 align:middle line:84%
Maybe you have to prove those
specially for some reason.

00:59:55.900 --> 01:00:01.120 align:middle line:90%
Then we do an induction step.

01:00:01.120 --> 01:00:03.115 align:middle line:90%
So I'll say by cases here.

01:00:03.115 --> 01:00:06.250 align:middle line:90%


01:00:06.250 --> 01:00:10.810 align:middle line:84%
Induction step we
get to assume n

01:00:10.810 --> 01:00:15.520 align:middle line:84%
is bigger than b because we
just proved 0 up to b manually.

01:00:15.520 --> 01:00:19.090 align:middle line:84%
And then we need to prove,
in those scenarios, P of n

01:00:19.090 --> 01:00:22.590 align:middle line:90%
is true because reasons.

01:00:22.590 --> 01:00:25.870 align:middle line:90%


01:00:25.870 --> 01:00:28.930 align:middle line:84%
But the big thing here
is we get to assume,

01:00:28.930 --> 01:00:41.280 align:middle line:84%
in these reasons we get to
use P0, P1, up to P n minus 1.

01:00:41.280 --> 01:00:46.450 align:middle line:90%


01:00:46.450 --> 01:00:48.860 align:middle line:90%
So that's the big win.

01:00:48.860 --> 01:00:52.890 align:middle line:84%
And in the base cases, you
also get to assume this.

01:00:52.890 --> 01:00:55.390 align:middle line:84%
But for example, when you're
proving P0 you don't really get

01:00:55.390 --> 01:00:58.670 align:middle line:84%
to assume anything because
there are no smaller Pi's.

01:00:58.670 --> 01:01:00.560 align:middle line:84%
So often, you have
to do these specially

01:01:00.560 --> 01:01:03.920 align:middle line:84%
because the induction
step assumes somehow

01:01:03.920 --> 01:01:06.493 align:middle line:90%
that n is bigger than 0.

01:01:06.493 --> 01:01:08.910 align:middle line:84%
Sometimes you get lucky, you
just need the induction step.

01:01:08.910 --> 01:01:10.530 align:middle line:90%
But usually you need base cases.

01:01:10.530 --> 01:01:11.940 align:middle line:90%
Let's see some examples.

01:01:11.940 --> 01:01:14.900 align:middle line:84%
And this will
become much clearer.

01:01:14.900 --> 01:01:21.460 align:middle line:84%
So let's play a game
called item stacking.

01:01:21.460 --> 01:01:24.470 align:middle line:90%


01:01:24.470 --> 01:01:25.716 align:middle line:90%
Or it's really unstacking.

01:01:25.716 --> 01:01:32.570 align:middle line:90%


01:01:32.570 --> 01:01:41.680 align:middle line:90%
So this is unstacking game.

01:01:41.680 --> 01:01:51.620 align:middle line:90%


01:01:51.620 --> 01:02:00.070 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to start
with one stack of n,

01:02:00.070 --> 01:02:11.830 align:middle line:84%
and then a move
splits a stack of S

01:02:11.830 --> 01:02:24.550 align:middle line:84%
bigger than 1 items into two
stacks with a items in one

01:02:24.550 --> 01:02:25.830 align:middle line:90%
and b items in the other.

01:02:25.830 --> 01:02:29.950 align:middle line:90%


01:02:29.950 --> 01:02:33.730 align:middle line:84%
And you get to choose
these numbers a and b,

01:02:33.730 --> 01:02:35.420 align:middle line:90%
but you need conservation.

01:02:35.420 --> 01:02:40.660 align:middle line:84%
So a plus b has to
equal S. And we also

01:02:40.660 --> 01:02:43.010 align:middle line:90%
don't want 0 height stacks.

01:02:43.010 --> 01:02:46.330 align:middle line:84%
So we need a at least
one and b at least one.

01:02:46.330 --> 01:02:48.040 align:middle line:84%
And so you get to
choose a and b however

01:02:48.040 --> 01:02:51.260 align:middle line:84%
you want so long as there's at
least one item in each stack.

01:02:51.260 --> 01:02:53.823 align:middle line:84%
So let's take a
physical example.

01:02:53.823 --> 01:02:57.310 align:middle line:90%


01:02:57.310 --> 01:03:00.590 align:middle line:84%
I've got lots of blocks
here, but I have no audience.

01:03:00.590 --> 01:03:03.730 align:middle line:84%
So we're just going
to demo this myself.

01:03:03.730 --> 01:03:08.660 align:middle line:84%
In real life, this is actually--
this was a snow day at MIT,

01:03:08.660 --> 01:03:10.430 align:middle line:84%
and so we're recording
after the fact.

01:03:10.430 --> 01:03:11.540 align:middle line:90%
So all the students--

01:03:11.540 --> 01:03:12.830 align:middle line:90%
MIT students have seen it.

01:03:12.830 --> 01:03:16.240 align:middle line:84%
This is specially
for you at OCW.

01:03:16.240 --> 01:03:19.600 align:middle line:90%
So when we do a move from S--

01:03:19.600 --> 01:03:21.790 align:middle line:84%
so this is-- we have
a stack of size S,

01:03:21.790 --> 01:03:24.760 align:middle line:84%
and we convert it into a stack
of size a and a stack of size b.

01:03:24.760 --> 01:03:27.913 align:middle line:90%
We get a times b points.

01:03:27.913 --> 01:03:31.390 align:middle line:90%


01:03:31.390 --> 01:03:33.368 align:middle line:84%
That's just the definition
of the game, a times

01:03:33.368 --> 01:03:35.410 align:middle line:84%
b points when you split
it into a stack of size a

01:03:35.410 --> 01:03:38.140 align:middle line:90%
and a stack of size b.

01:03:38.140 --> 01:03:42.620 align:middle line:84%
So how should I maximize
my score in this game?

01:03:42.620 --> 01:03:44.260 align:middle line:90%
What's the best strategy?

01:03:44.260 --> 01:03:46.150 align:middle line:84%
The game ends when
all your stacks

01:03:46.150 --> 01:03:48.490 align:middle line:84%
have size 1 because
you can't make

01:03:48.490 --> 01:03:50.320 align:middle line:90%
a move on a stack of one item.

01:03:50.320 --> 01:03:52.380 align:middle line:84%
It has to be greater
than 1 items.

01:03:52.380 --> 01:03:53.380 align:middle line:90%
So let's try.

01:03:53.380 --> 01:03:57.000 align:middle line:84%
Here I have a stack
of five blocks.

01:03:57.000 --> 01:04:00.660 align:middle line:84%
And one thing-- maybe I'll
try to split it roughly

01:04:00.660 --> 01:04:01.600 align:middle line:90%
in the middle.

01:04:01.600 --> 01:04:03.780 align:middle line:84%
So now-- here, I'll
rotate this so you can see

01:04:03.780 --> 01:04:05.130 align:middle line:90%
how it blocks a little bigger.

01:04:05.130 --> 01:04:06.750 align:middle line:90%
These are five blocks.

01:04:06.750 --> 01:04:08.590 align:middle line:90%
I split like this.

01:04:08.590 --> 01:04:10.950 align:middle line:84%
So that's a group of
2 and a group of 3.

01:04:10.950 --> 01:04:12.720 align:middle line:90%
Product of 2 times 3 is 6.

01:04:12.720 --> 01:04:14.470 align:middle line:84%
I can do this level
of arithmetic.

01:04:14.470 --> 01:04:16.630 align:middle line:90%
So 6 is our total so far.

01:04:16.630 --> 01:04:20.020 align:middle line:84%
When I split this one,
I get one more point.

01:04:20.020 --> 01:04:20.880 align:middle line:90%
That's 7.

01:04:20.880 --> 01:04:24.070 align:middle line:84%
When I split this one,
doesn't matter how I do it,

01:04:24.070 --> 01:04:26.800 align:middle line:90%
I get 2 times 1.

01:04:26.800 --> 01:04:28.240 align:middle line:90%
So that's two more points.

01:04:28.240 --> 01:04:30.040 align:middle line:90%
That's 9.

01:04:30.040 --> 01:04:34.000 align:middle line:84%
And when I split this
group, I get one more point.

01:04:34.000 --> 01:04:35.510 align:middle line:90%
That's 10.

01:04:35.510 --> 01:04:36.010 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:04:36.010 --> 01:04:38.680 align:middle line:84%
So one approach
gives me 10 points.

01:04:38.680 --> 01:04:40.847 align:middle line:84%
What if-- another
natural strategy.

01:04:40.847 --> 01:04:42.430 align:middle line:84%
That was like splitting
in the middle.

01:04:42.430 --> 01:04:45.540 align:middle line:84%
Another natural strategy is I
just take one off each time.

01:04:45.540 --> 01:04:49.650 align:middle line:84%
So if I take one off
here, I get 4 points.

01:04:49.650 --> 01:04:52.360 align:middle line:84%
If I take one more off,
I get 3 more points.

01:04:52.360 --> 01:04:54.030 align:middle line:90%
That's 7.

01:04:54.030 --> 01:04:55.422 align:middle line:90%
4 plus 3 is 7.

01:04:55.422 --> 01:04:57.550 align:middle line:84%
I take one more
off, I get 2 points.

01:04:57.550 --> 01:04:58.920 align:middle line:90%
That's 9.

01:04:58.920 --> 01:05:00.570 align:middle line:90%
I take one more off.

01:05:00.570 --> 01:05:01.525 align:middle line:90%
That's one point.

01:05:01.525 --> 01:05:02.025 align:middle line:90%
That's 10.

01:05:02.025 --> 01:05:03.140 align:middle line:90%
Huh.

01:05:03.140 --> 01:05:05.950 align:middle line:84%
10 points that way, 10
points the other way as well?

01:05:05.950 --> 01:05:07.210 align:middle line:90%
Maybe there's a theorem here.

01:05:07.210 --> 01:05:09.310 align:middle line:84%
Maybe no matter what
I do, I get 10 points.

01:05:09.310 --> 01:05:10.690 align:middle line:90%
Well, that won't be true.

01:05:10.690 --> 01:05:13.630 align:middle line:84%
But for five blocks I
will always get 10 points.

01:05:13.630 --> 01:05:15.700 align:middle line:90%
For 6 blocks I will always get--

01:05:15.700 --> 01:05:16.530 align:middle line:90%
I don't know--

01:05:16.530 --> 01:05:17.430 align:middle line:90%
15.

01:05:17.430 --> 01:05:18.857 align:middle line:90%
Some more points.

01:05:18.857 --> 01:05:21.190 align:middle line:84%
It turns out it doesn't matter
what strategy you follow,

01:05:21.190 --> 01:05:23.490 align:middle line:84%
you always get the same
number of points for a given

01:05:23.490 --> 01:05:27.120 align:middle line:90%
initial stack of size n.

01:05:27.120 --> 01:05:30.250 align:middle line:84%
Let's prove that with
strong induction.

01:05:30.250 --> 01:05:33.830 align:middle line:90%


01:05:33.830 --> 01:05:34.330 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:05:34.330 --> 01:05:50.610 align:middle line:84%
So theorem is for all natural
numbers, every strategy

01:05:50.610 --> 01:06:10.290 align:middle line:84%
for this game starting with
the stack, one stack of n items

01:06:10.290 --> 01:06:13.230 align:middle line:90%
scores--

01:06:13.230 --> 01:06:16.715 align:middle line:84%
magic formula is n
times n minus 1 over 2.

01:06:16.715 --> 01:06:19.590 align:middle line:90%


01:06:19.590 --> 01:06:21.510 align:middle line:90%
So that's the theorem.

01:06:21.510 --> 01:06:30.240 align:middle line:84%
And we're going to prove
it by strong induction

01:06:30.240 --> 01:06:31.960 align:middle line:90%
in the straightforward way.

01:06:31.960 --> 01:06:34.830 align:middle line:84%
So our induction hypothesis is
going to be exactly the theorem

01:06:34.830 --> 01:06:37.000 align:middle line:90%
statement for a particular n.

01:06:37.000 --> 01:06:42.180 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to highlight
this statement, everything

01:06:42.180 --> 01:06:43.630 align:middle line:90%
except the quantifier.

01:06:43.630 --> 01:06:45.330 align:middle line:90%
And I'll call that P of n.

01:06:45.330 --> 01:06:48.900 align:middle line:84%
So what I wanted to prove is
for all natural numbers n P of n

01:06:48.900 --> 01:06:49.890 align:middle line:90%
is true.

01:06:49.890 --> 01:06:52.480 align:middle line:84%
And so that's just going to
be our induction hypothesis.

01:06:52.480 --> 01:06:54.700 align:middle line:84%
We're going to plug that
into this template here.

01:06:54.700 --> 01:06:57.930 align:middle line:84%
Assume that P of k is true
for all k less than n,

01:06:57.930 --> 01:07:00.070 align:middle line:90%
and then prove P of n is true.

01:07:00.070 --> 01:07:03.690 align:middle line:90%
So let's just try to do that.

01:07:03.690 --> 01:07:08.830 align:middle line:84%
So what I would normally
write here is assume true--

01:07:08.830 --> 01:07:10.240 align:middle line:90%
assume that my theorem is true.

01:07:10.240 --> 01:07:12.480 align:middle line:90%
Assume P of n is true.

01:07:12.480 --> 01:07:14.070 align:middle line:90%
Sorry.

01:07:14.070 --> 01:07:18.270 align:middle line:84%
P of k is true for
all k less than n.

01:07:18.270 --> 01:07:20.720 align:middle line:84%
I would say assume
true for all smaller n.

01:07:20.720 --> 01:07:30.003 align:middle line:90%


01:07:30.003 --> 01:07:30.503 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:07:30.503 --> 01:07:33.210 align:middle line:90%


01:07:33.210 --> 01:07:35.650 align:middle line:84%
We need to do something
with the game.

01:07:35.650 --> 01:07:37.420 align:middle line:90%
We start with a pile of size n.

01:07:37.420 --> 01:07:40.410 align:middle line:84%
Let's just think
about the first move.

01:07:40.410 --> 01:07:41.940 align:middle line:90%
First move is something.

01:07:41.940 --> 01:07:44.370 align:middle line:84%
It takes our pile of
size n, and it splits it

01:07:44.370 --> 01:07:46.950 align:middle line:90%
into some piles a and b.

01:07:46.950 --> 01:07:49.990 align:middle line:90%
So we don't know what it is.

01:07:49.990 --> 01:07:53.700 align:middle line:84%
We don't know what a and b are,
but we can give them a name.

01:07:53.700 --> 01:07:55.980 align:middle line:84%
This has to work no
matter what a and b are.

01:07:55.980 --> 01:07:59.530 align:middle line:84%
But let's say consider
first move, which we know

01:07:59.530 --> 01:08:01.110 align:middle line:90%
we start with a pile of size n.

01:08:01.110 --> 01:08:04.470 align:middle line:84%
And we produce piles
of size a and b.

01:08:04.470 --> 01:08:10.823 align:middle line:84%
And again, a plus b equals n,
and a and b are at least 1.

01:08:10.823 --> 01:08:12.740 align:middle line:84%
But otherwise, we don't
know what a and b are.

01:08:12.740 --> 01:08:35.729 align:middle line:90%


01:08:35.729 --> 01:08:37.673 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:08:37.673 --> 01:08:39.214 align:middle line:90%
So we go down here.

01:08:39.214 --> 01:08:41.850 align:middle line:90%


01:08:41.850 --> 01:08:46.847 align:middle line:84%
So we now have a pile of size
a, and we have a pile of size b.

01:08:46.847 --> 01:08:48.430 align:middle line:84%
Again, we don't know
how big they are,

01:08:48.430 --> 01:08:50.350 align:middle line:90%
but they are smaller than b.

01:08:50.350 --> 01:08:56.710 align:middle line:84%
So I want to claim we
are left with two piles.

01:08:56.710 --> 01:08:59.460 align:middle line:84%
Or we can really think of those
as two completely separate

01:08:59.460 --> 01:09:02.978 align:middle line:90%
games, a and b.

01:09:02.978 --> 01:09:05.020 align:middle line:84%
We're going to get some
points from splitting up.

01:09:05.020 --> 01:09:07.145 align:middle line:84%
We're going to get some
points from splitting up b.

01:09:07.145 --> 01:09:08.290 align:middle line:90%
They sum together.

01:09:08.290 --> 01:09:11.170 align:middle line:84%
But these piles don't really
interact from here on.

01:09:11.170 --> 01:09:17.308 align:middle line:84%
We got a times b points
from this first step.

01:09:17.308 --> 01:09:19.600 align:middle line:84%
We're going to get some points
from the pile of size a.

01:09:19.600 --> 01:09:21.808 align:middle line:84%
We're going to get some
points to the pile of size b.

01:09:21.808 --> 01:09:23.819 align:middle line:90%
How many points do we get?

01:09:23.819 --> 01:09:25.529 align:middle line:84%
Well, in fact, our
induction hypothesis

01:09:25.529 --> 01:09:32.010 align:middle line:84%
will tell us because a and
b are strictly less than n.

01:09:32.010 --> 01:09:33.149 align:middle line:90%
Why?

01:09:33.149 --> 01:09:41.409 align:middle line:84%
Because a plus b equals n,
and a and b are at least 1.

01:09:41.409 --> 01:09:44.060 align:middle line:90%


01:09:44.060 --> 01:09:46.460 align:middle line:84%
So there's at least
1 in each of a and b.

01:09:46.460 --> 01:09:49.880 align:middle line:84%
And so the remainder must
be strictly less than n.

01:09:49.880 --> 01:09:52.580 align:middle line:84%
If there's one in a, then
there'll be n minus 1 in b.

01:09:52.580 --> 01:09:55.610 align:middle line:84%
If there's two in a, there'll
be n minus 2 in b, in all cases

01:09:55.610 --> 01:09:57.470 align:middle line:90%
less than n.

01:09:57.470 --> 01:09:59.870 align:middle line:84%
Because a and b are
less than n, they're

01:09:59.870 --> 01:10:01.230 align:middle line:90%
not necessarily n minus 1.

01:10:01.230 --> 01:10:03.080 align:middle line:84%
So we couldn't just
use regular induction.

01:10:03.080 --> 01:10:05.280 align:middle line:90%
But they're less than n.

01:10:05.280 --> 01:10:12.080 align:middle line:84%
And so by strong induction,
by strong induction,

01:10:12.080 --> 01:10:16.930 align:middle line:84%
we know that P of a is
true, and P of b is true.

01:10:16.930 --> 01:10:20.030 align:middle line:90%


01:10:20.030 --> 01:10:24.080 align:middle line:84%
We wrote that up here, some
P of k for all k less than n.

01:10:24.080 --> 01:10:27.500 align:middle line:84%
So a and b are less than n,
so P of a is true, and P of b

01:10:27.500 --> 01:10:28.410 align:middle line:90%
is true.

01:10:28.410 --> 01:10:37.040 align:middle line:84%
So that means, from the pile of
size a we get a times a minus 1

01:10:37.040 --> 01:10:38.253 align:middle line:90%
over 2 points.

01:10:38.253 --> 01:10:43.340 align:middle line:90%


01:10:43.340 --> 01:10:49.460 align:middle line:84%
From the a pile we get b
times b minus 1 over 2 points

01:10:49.460 --> 01:10:53.150 align:middle line:90%
from the b pile.

01:10:53.150 --> 01:10:57.650 align:middle line:84%
And then, of course,
we got a times b points

01:10:57.650 --> 01:10:58.900 align:middle line:90%
from the first move.

01:10:58.900 --> 01:11:06.020 align:middle line:90%


01:11:06.020 --> 01:11:08.300 align:middle line:84%
And so now we just
need to do some algebra

01:11:08.300 --> 01:11:10.520 align:middle line:90%
and add up all these points.

01:11:10.520 --> 01:11:14.420 align:middle line:84%
So the total number
of points that we get

01:11:14.420 --> 01:11:19.370 align:middle line:84%
is a times b plus a
times a minus 1 over 2

01:11:19.370 --> 01:11:23.270 align:middle line:90%
plus b times b minus 1 over 2.

01:11:23.270 --> 01:11:24.510 align:middle line:90%
These two were by induction.

01:11:24.510 --> 01:11:26.180 align:middle line:90%
This was the first move.

01:11:26.180 --> 01:11:28.230 align:middle line:84%
And now let's just
put everything over 2.

01:11:28.230 --> 01:11:33.290 align:middle line:84%
So this is 2 times a times b
plus a squared minus a plus

01:11:33.290 --> 01:11:38.120 align:middle line:90%
b squared minus b all over 2.

01:11:38.120 --> 01:11:41.100 align:middle line:84%
And now, what do
I want to get to?

01:11:41.100 --> 01:11:45.230 align:middle line:84%
This is supposed to equal
n times n minus 1 over 2.

01:11:45.230 --> 01:11:46.580 align:middle line:90%
And what was n?

01:11:46.580 --> 01:11:50.360 align:middle line:90%
n was a plus b.

01:11:50.360 --> 01:11:52.310 align:middle line:84%
So what I'd really
like to show here

01:11:52.310 --> 01:12:00.240 align:middle line:84%
is a plus b times a
plus b minus 1 over 2.

01:12:00.240 --> 01:12:01.620 align:middle line:90%
That's my goal.

01:12:01.620 --> 01:12:03.846 align:middle line:84%
And what I need to do is
fill in the in-between.

01:12:03.846 --> 01:12:06.740 align:middle line:90%


01:12:06.740 --> 01:12:11.810 align:middle line:84%
But this is not too hard
because, let's see, I

01:12:11.810 --> 01:12:16.980 align:middle line:84%
see a times b here
and a times b here.

01:12:16.980 --> 01:12:18.860 align:middle line:84%
In fact, you can
just expand this out,

01:12:18.860 --> 01:12:21.320 align:middle line:84%
and you'll get exactly
the same thing here.

01:12:21.320 --> 01:12:23.280 align:middle line:84%
I think slightly more
intuitive is to see,

01:12:23.280 --> 01:12:26.960 align:middle line:84%
oh, look at this term,
this term, and this term.

01:12:26.960 --> 01:12:33.680 align:middle line:84%
That is a squared plus
2ab plus b squared.

01:12:33.680 --> 01:12:36.090 align:middle line:90%
That is a plus b squared.

01:12:36.090 --> 01:12:39.920 align:middle line:84%
And then we have a
minus a, minus b over 2.

01:12:39.920 --> 01:12:42.470 align:middle line:90%
But interject a rule in between.

01:12:42.470 --> 01:12:49.640 align:middle line:84%
We have a plus b squared
minus a plus b over 2.

01:12:49.640 --> 01:12:51.830 align:middle line:84%
And then these two
are the same thing.

01:12:51.830 --> 01:12:53.780 align:middle line:90%
I think that's pretty clear.

01:12:53.780 --> 01:12:54.660 align:middle line:90%
So cool.

01:12:54.660 --> 01:12:57.470 align:middle line:84%
We did some algebra,
and we just computed

01:12:57.470 --> 01:12:59.040 align:middle line:90%
what we get out of induction.

01:12:59.040 --> 01:12:59.930 align:middle line:90%
And then boom!

01:12:59.930 --> 01:13:02.190 align:middle line:84%
We get the answer n
times n minus 1 over 2.

01:13:02.190 --> 01:13:02.970 align:middle line:90%
And it works.

01:13:02.970 --> 01:13:04.790 align:middle line:84%
How did we know this
is the right answer?

01:13:04.790 --> 01:13:07.670 align:middle line:84%
We were just told
that by the theorem.

01:13:07.670 --> 01:13:09.920 align:middle line:84%
Probably, you would try
this for very small n

01:13:09.920 --> 01:13:11.040 align:middle line:90%
and make a conjecture.

01:13:11.040 --> 01:13:13.350 align:middle line:84%
Oh, it seems like it's n
times n minus 1 over 2.

01:13:13.350 --> 01:13:14.700 align:middle line:90%
Let's try to prove it.

01:13:14.700 --> 01:13:17.810 align:middle line:84%
And when you assume the right
thing, the proof just works.

01:13:17.810 --> 01:13:19.050 align:middle line:90%
And it's kind of magical.

01:13:19.050 --> 01:13:20.907 align:middle line:90%
And that's strong induction.

01:13:20.907 --> 01:13:22.490 align:middle line:84%
Again, we need a
strong induction here

01:13:22.490 --> 01:13:26.960 align:middle line:84%
because we need to assume what
we wanted for all smaller n

01:13:26.960 --> 01:13:29.130 align:middle line:84%
because we don't know
what a and b are.

01:13:29.130 --> 01:13:35.030 align:middle line:84%
This has to work for
all a and b less than n.

01:13:35.030 --> 01:13:40.370 align:middle line:84%
So luckily, strong
induction gives us that.

01:13:40.370 --> 01:13:43.280 align:middle line:84%
All right, I have
one more example

01:13:43.280 --> 01:13:50.060 align:middle line:84%
to tell you about, a slightly
more complicated version

01:13:50.060 --> 01:13:51.330 align:middle line:90%
of the same thing.

01:13:51.330 --> 01:13:53.940 align:middle line:84%
We're going to use
strong induction.

01:13:53.940 --> 01:13:54.940 align:middle line:90%
Don't need any of these.

01:13:54.940 --> 01:13:57.710 align:middle line:90%


01:13:57.710 --> 01:14:00.130 align:middle line:90%
So let's go.

01:14:00.130 --> 01:14:03.830 align:middle line:90%


01:14:03.830 --> 01:14:06.850 align:middle line:84%
This is the problem
called Beat Ordering.

01:14:06.850 --> 01:14:09.710 align:middle line:90%


01:14:09.710 --> 01:14:14.130 align:middle line:84%
I guess somewhat relevant today
because it was the Super Bowl.

01:14:14.130 --> 01:14:18.750 align:middle line:84%
But this is just about
any teams of games.

01:14:18.750 --> 01:14:19.340 align:middle line:90%
Sorry.

01:14:19.340 --> 01:14:21.080 align:middle line:90%
n teams in some game.

01:14:21.080 --> 01:14:27.170 align:middle line:84%
And setup is that every
two teams play a game,

01:14:27.170 --> 01:14:28.930 align:middle line:90%
and there are no ties.

01:14:28.930 --> 01:14:33.320 align:middle line:90%


01:14:33.320 --> 01:14:39.970 align:middle line:84%
One team wins, and
the other loses.

01:14:39.970 --> 01:14:40.470 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:14:40.470 --> 01:14:43.962 align:middle line:84%
This is like friends
and strangers,

01:14:43.962 --> 01:14:45.420 align:middle line:84%
where it's either
one or the other.

01:14:45.420 --> 01:14:47.550 align:middle line:84%
But in this case,
it's asymmetric.

01:14:47.550 --> 01:14:49.410 align:middle line:84%
They're not both
happy or both sad.

01:14:49.410 --> 01:14:52.000 align:middle line:90%
One is happy, and one is sad.

01:14:52.000 --> 01:14:52.500 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:14:52.500 --> 01:14:54.512 align:middle line:84%
This is what's called a
Round Robin tournament.

01:14:54.512 --> 01:14:55.970 align:middle line:84%
Most sports are
not played this way

01:14:55.970 --> 01:14:58.028 align:middle line:84%
unless a small number
of teams because it's

01:14:58.028 --> 01:14:59.070 align:middle line:90%
a lot of different teams.

01:14:59.070 --> 01:15:02.510 align:middle line:84%
It's actually n times
n plus 1 over 2 teams

01:15:02.510 --> 01:15:04.670 align:middle line:90%
games, which is a lot.

01:15:04.670 --> 01:15:08.343 align:middle line:84%
All right, so what
we would like is

01:15:08.343 --> 01:15:09.593 align:middle line:90%
what's called a beat ordering.

01:15:09.593 --> 01:15:12.590 align:middle line:90%


01:15:12.590 --> 01:15:24.830 align:middle line:84%
This is an ordering of the
teams T1, T2, up to Tn,

01:15:24.830 --> 01:15:32.260 align:middle line:90%
such that B1 beat--

01:15:32.260 --> 01:15:34.220 align:middle line:90%
sorry, T1, T for teams.

01:15:34.220 --> 01:15:36.410 align:middle line:90%
T1 beats T2.

01:15:36.410 --> 01:15:40.720 align:middle line:90%
T2 beat T3, and so on.

01:15:40.720 --> 01:15:45.600 align:middle line:90%
And Tn minus 1 beats Tn.

01:15:45.600 --> 01:15:46.100 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:15:46.100 --> 01:15:48.730 align:middle line:90%
Let's draw a little example.

01:15:48.730 --> 01:15:56.230 align:middle line:84%
There's team rock, team
scissors, and team paper.

01:15:56.230 --> 01:15:56.750 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:15:56.750 --> 01:15:58.310 align:middle line:90%
Paper beats rock.

01:15:58.310 --> 01:15:59.660 align:middle line:90%
Rock beats scissors.

01:15:59.660 --> 01:16:01.160 align:middle line:90%
Scissors beats paper.

01:16:01.160 --> 01:16:01.660 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:16:01.660 --> 01:16:05.420 align:middle line:84%
This is a possible outcome
in a three-team tournament.

01:16:05.420 --> 01:16:08.270 align:middle line:84%
There's not necessarily
one best team here.

01:16:08.270 --> 01:16:09.560 align:middle line:90%
There is no best team.

01:16:09.560 --> 01:16:11.560 align:middle line:84%
But maybe paper and
rock play a game, And.

01:16:11.560 --> 01:16:12.950 align:middle line:90%
It happens that paper won.

01:16:12.950 --> 01:16:15.430 align:middle line:84%
Maybe rock plays
against scissors,

01:16:15.430 --> 01:16:16.473 align:middle line:90%
and it happens rock won.

01:16:16.473 --> 01:16:17.890 align:middle line:84%
And scissors played
against paper,

01:16:17.890 --> 01:16:19.640 align:middle line:90%
and it happens scissors won.

01:16:19.640 --> 01:16:20.180 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:16:20.180 --> 01:16:23.470 align:middle line:84%
You can tell why I named
the teams this way.

01:16:23.470 --> 01:16:25.630 align:middle line:84%
Then one way I could
order these teams

01:16:25.630 --> 01:16:33.770 align:middle line:84%
is paper, rock, scissors
because paper beats rock.

01:16:33.770 --> 01:16:35.370 align:middle line:90%
Rock beats scissors.

01:16:35.370 --> 01:16:35.870 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:16:35.870 --> 01:16:37.960 align:middle line:90%
So this is the input.

01:16:37.960 --> 01:16:42.650 align:middle line:84%
And this is my goal is to
produce an ordering like this.

01:16:42.650 --> 01:16:46.630 align:middle line:84%
But I need to do it for n
teams, not just for three.

01:16:46.630 --> 01:16:58.030 align:middle line:84%
So let's do strong induction
to prove that the theorem is

01:16:58.030 --> 01:16:59.865 align:middle line:90%
a beat ordering always exists.

01:16:59.865 --> 01:17:06.770 align:middle line:90%


01:17:06.770 --> 01:17:07.270 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:17:07.270 --> 01:17:10.930 align:middle line:90%


01:17:10.930 --> 01:17:11.430 align:middle line:90%
Theorem.

01:17:11.430 --> 01:17:20.860 align:middle line:90%


01:17:20.860 --> 01:17:23.590 align:middle line:84%
And when I say this always
exists, what I really mean

01:17:23.590 --> 01:17:32.380 align:middle line:84%
is for all n and then for
all tournaments of size

01:17:32.380 --> 01:17:42.740 align:middle line:90%
n there exists a beat order.

01:17:42.740 --> 01:17:43.240 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:17:43.240 --> 01:17:44.860 align:middle line:84%
There exists an
ordering of the n teams

01:17:44.860 --> 01:17:46.370 align:middle line:84%
such that the first one
beat the second one,

01:17:46.370 --> 01:17:48.260 align:middle line:84%
the second one beat the
third one, and so on.

01:17:48.260 --> 01:17:56.910 align:middle line:84%
I should say, for all
i Ti beat Ti plus 1.

01:17:56.910 --> 01:17:59.440 align:middle line:90%


01:17:59.440 --> 01:18:02.710 align:middle line:90%
So we claim this is true.

01:18:02.710 --> 01:18:05.720 align:middle line:90%
Proof by strong induction.

01:18:05.720 --> 01:18:09.610 align:middle line:90%


01:18:09.610 --> 01:18:13.610 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to assume
that this statement is true.

01:18:13.610 --> 01:18:20.770 align:middle line:84%
Namely, this statement
is true for smaller n.

01:18:20.770 --> 01:18:22.440 align:middle line:84%
And then we're going
to prove it for n.

01:18:22.440 --> 01:18:26.050 align:middle line:90%


01:18:26.050 --> 01:18:27.670 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:18:27.670 --> 01:18:34.510 align:middle line:90%
Let's pick a team, any team.

01:18:34.510 --> 01:18:38.980 align:middle line:84%
Call it T. Then I'm
going to split everything

01:18:38.980 --> 01:18:40.070 align:middle line:90%
with respect to t.

01:18:40.070 --> 01:18:45.250 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to define W
to be the set of teams that

01:18:45.250 --> 01:18:50.090 align:middle line:84%
win against T. So this is going
to be a set of all teams S

01:18:50.090 --> 01:18:59.890 align:middle line:84%
where S beat T. So this is
1 versus T. These teams win

01:18:59.890 --> 01:19:04.090 align:middle line:84%
versus T or 1 versus T. And L
is going to be the set of teams

01:19:04.090 --> 01:19:08.723 align:middle line:84%
that lose against T. So this is
the set of teams S where TBS.

01:19:08.723 --> 01:19:11.560 align:middle line:90%


01:19:11.560 --> 01:19:16.210 align:middle line:90%
So this is a loss versus T.

01:19:16.210 --> 01:19:17.710 align:middle line:84%
Then, intuitively,
what we'd like

01:19:17.710 --> 01:19:23.690 align:middle line:84%
to do is put the winners first,
then put T, then put the losers.

01:19:23.690 --> 01:19:26.160 align:middle line:90%
I claim that works, OK?

01:19:26.160 --> 01:19:28.110 align:middle line:90%
But how do I order the winners?

01:19:28.110 --> 01:19:30.080 align:middle line:90%
How do I order the losers?

01:19:30.080 --> 01:19:32.600 align:middle line:90%
Well, by induction.

01:19:32.600 --> 01:19:35.670 align:middle line:90%
I claim the size of W--

01:19:35.670 --> 01:19:38.060 align:middle line:84%
this vertical bar means
the size of the set--

01:19:38.060 --> 01:19:40.700 align:middle line:90%
is less than n.

01:19:40.700 --> 01:19:49.010 align:middle line:84%
And the size of L is less
than n because the size

01:19:49.010 --> 01:19:55.220 align:middle line:84%
of the winners plus the size
of the losers plus 1 equals n.

01:19:55.220 --> 01:19:56.690 align:middle line:90%
This is a 1.

01:19:56.690 --> 01:19:57.380 align:middle line:90%
Why?

01:19:57.380 --> 01:20:01.070 align:middle line:84%
Because every team is either
T, or they won against T,

01:20:01.070 --> 01:20:04.740 align:middle line:84%
or they lost against T. So this
is counting all of the teams.

01:20:04.740 --> 01:20:06.930 align:middle line:84%
There's T itself, the
ones that win against T,

01:20:06.930 --> 01:20:10.850 align:middle line:84%
the ones that lose against T.
Together, that is exactly n.

01:20:10.850 --> 01:20:14.330 align:middle line:84%
Every team is exactly
one of these categories.

01:20:14.330 --> 01:20:16.990 align:middle line:90%
And there's a plus 1 here.

01:20:16.990 --> 01:20:19.660 align:middle line:84%
And all of these
are non-negative.

01:20:19.660 --> 01:20:22.510 align:middle line:84%
Here, W and L might be 0,
but there's this plus 1.

01:20:22.510 --> 01:20:25.780 align:middle line:84%
That means both W and L
are strictly less than n.

01:20:25.780 --> 01:20:30.910 align:middle line:84%
So the induction
applies to them.

01:20:30.910 --> 01:20:34.630 align:middle line:90%
So by induction.

01:20:34.630 --> 01:20:38.110 align:middle line:84%
This thing is true for
any tournament of size W

01:20:38.110 --> 01:20:41.590 align:middle line:84%
there exists a bit ordering of
W. For every tournament of size

01:20:41.590 --> 01:20:50.950 align:middle line:84%
L there exists a beat ordering
of L. So we get a beat ordering.

01:20:50.950 --> 01:20:53.470 align:middle line:90%
We get two of them, really.

01:20:53.470 --> 01:21:03.860 align:middle line:84%
Let's call it W1, W2, dot, dot,
dot W size of W. This is for--

01:21:03.860 --> 01:21:09.800 align:middle line:84%
this is an ordering of capital
W. And we get L1, L2, dot,

01:21:09.800 --> 01:21:16.380 align:middle line:84%
dot, dot, L size of L as a
beat ordering of capital L.

01:21:16.380 --> 01:21:20.910 align:middle line:90%
And then, we concatenate.

01:21:20.910 --> 01:21:33.090 align:middle line:84%
So we claim W1, dot,
dot, dot W size of w,

01:21:33.090 --> 01:21:42.270 align:middle line:84%
then T, then L1, dot,
dot, dot L size of L

01:21:42.270 --> 01:21:49.110 align:middle line:84%
is a beat ordering
of all n teams.

01:21:49.110 --> 01:21:50.470 align:middle line:90%
Again, this is all the teams.

01:21:50.470 --> 01:21:53.370 align:middle line:84%
All the teams either won
against T, or they are T,

01:21:53.370 --> 01:21:55.210 align:middle line:90%
or they lost against t.

01:21:55.210 --> 01:21:57.480 align:middle line:84%
And the idea is
this part is beat.

01:21:57.480 --> 01:22:00.700 align:middle line:84%
W1 beats W2, W2
beats W3, and so on,

01:22:00.700 --> 01:22:03.930 align:middle line:84%
by induction because
this is a beat ordering

01:22:03.930 --> 01:22:09.640 align:middle line:84%
of capital W. Over here, this
is a beat ordering of capital L.

01:22:09.640 --> 01:22:13.780 align:middle line:84%
And so by induction
all these are OK.

01:22:13.780 --> 01:22:14.730 align:middle line:90%
L1 beat L2.

01:22:14.730 --> 01:22:18.610 align:middle line:84%
L2 beat so on, dot, dot,
dot beat L size of L.

01:22:18.610 --> 01:22:21.340 align:middle line:84%
The only things we need to
check are these two commas.

01:22:21.340 --> 01:22:24.510 align:middle line:84%
We need to check
that W sub big W--

01:22:24.510 --> 01:22:29.470 align:middle line:84%
W sub size of W beats
T, and T beat L1.

01:22:29.470 --> 01:22:31.320 align:middle line:90%
Why are those true?

01:22:31.320 --> 01:22:35.340 align:middle line:84%
By our definition of W
and L. Everything in W

01:22:35.340 --> 01:22:41.730 align:middle line:84%
beat T. So this is by
the definition of W. We

01:22:41.730 --> 01:22:44.490 align:middle line:90%
know that all of these beat T.

01:22:44.490 --> 01:22:46.620 align:middle line:84%
So in particular,
this one beat T.

01:22:46.620 --> 01:22:52.380 align:middle line:84%
And we know by the
definition of L

01:22:52.380 --> 01:22:55.020 align:middle line:84%
all of these teams lost
against T. In other words,

01:22:55.020 --> 01:22:57.660 align:middle line:90%
T beats all of these teams.

01:22:57.660 --> 01:23:00.300 align:middle line:90%
And in particular, T beat L1.

01:23:00.300 --> 01:23:03.040 align:middle line:84%
And so by combining all these
beat statements together,

01:23:03.040 --> 01:23:06.160 align:middle line:84%
we know that this entire
thing is a beat ordering.

01:23:06.160 --> 01:23:08.740 align:middle line:84%
Each item beats the
one right after it.

01:23:08.740 --> 01:23:10.570 align:middle line:84%
So it's a little
more complicated.

01:23:10.570 --> 01:23:15.850 align:middle line:84%
But again, we're d quite often
with strong induction proofs,

01:23:15.850 --> 01:23:17.530 align:middle line:90%
you apply induction twice.

01:23:17.530 --> 01:23:19.060 align:middle line:84%
You have some
problem with size n.

01:23:19.060 --> 01:23:20.252 align:middle line:90%
You split it into two parts.

01:23:20.252 --> 01:23:22.210 align:middle line:84%
In general, you might
split it into many parts.

01:23:22.210 --> 01:23:25.870 align:middle line:84%
Then you recursively solve the
two parts or the many parts,

01:23:25.870 --> 01:23:28.110 align:middle line:84%
as long as they're
strictly smaller than n.

01:23:28.110 --> 01:23:31.020 align:middle line:84%
By induction, we
know they work out.

01:23:31.020 --> 01:23:32.950 align:middle line:84%
By strong induction,
we know they work out.

01:23:32.950 --> 01:23:35.470 align:middle line:84%
You take those solutions and
you combine them in some way.

01:23:35.470 --> 01:23:38.940 align:middle line:84%
Here, we concatenated
with T in the middle.

01:23:38.940 --> 01:23:42.215 align:middle line:90%
Over here, we summed them up.

01:23:42.215 --> 01:23:43.590 align:middle line:84%
We summed up the
number of points

01:23:43.590 --> 01:23:45.540 align:middle line:84%
we got in each one plus
the number of points

01:23:45.540 --> 01:23:48.345 align:middle line:90%
we got in the first step.

01:23:48.345 --> 01:23:50.220 align:middle line:84%
And in general, you
combine them in some way,

01:23:50.220 --> 01:23:54.840 align:middle line:84%
and you prove that the thing you
want to prove holds for size n.

01:23:54.840 --> 01:23:56.290 align:middle line:90%
And then you get your theorem.

01:23:56.290 --> 01:24:00.390 align:middle line:84%
So that is the power
of strong induction.

01:24:00.390 --> 01:24:01.970 align:middle line:90%
Thanks.

01:24:01.970 --> 01:24:10.000 align:middle line:90%